<HEAD>AP Board Approves 4.4 Percent Assessment Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The board of directors of The Associated Press approved unanimously a 1989 general assessment increase of 4.4 percent for newspaper and broadcast members. The increase takes effect Jan. 15, 1989, for <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s 1,463 newspaper and 5,700 broadcast members. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keating </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> board chairman and chief executive officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, noted that the increase was below inflation estimates of 5 percent to 5.5 percent for next year. `` The increase continues the recent trend of assessment adjustments less than the general rate of inflation,'' he said Tuesday. <PERSON> Keating </PERSON> said `` stringent cost controls and new revenues from nonmember sources'' enabled the board to restrict the increase to 4.4 percent and still fund major service improvements now under way. <PERSON> Keating </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s proposed operating and capital budgets were examined by the board on a detailed, line-by-line basis. The budgets provide for expansion of <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s news staff, mostly in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, to help meet the needs of <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s 28 percent increase in newspaper membership over the past five years, <PERSON> Keating </PERSON> said. The budgets also provide support for the new high-speed PhotoStream and GraphicsNet systems, as well as for total replacement of editing systems in all domestic bureaus. The general assessment increase will be combined with the fifth step of the phase-in of the circulation-based newspaper formula for those not yet on card with the new formula, which was adopted in 1985. Changes in circulation will also be reflected in the new assessment for each newspaper member. Each member will receive exact figures on the assessment change in October, <PERSON> Keating </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
