<HEAD>School Board President Says He Lies To Uncover Leaks</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with mayor removing board president,
comments from Hollis new conference.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayor <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmoke </PERSON> removed the <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> president on Tuesday after he admitted lying to board members as a way of finding out who leaks stories to the media. <PERSON> Meldon </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON>, who was appointed by the mayor to a one-year term as board president in December, will remain on the board. The mayor appoints the nine board members, who serve as volunteers. <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON>, an attorney, admitted earlier Tuesday that he used poor judgment in planting three different versions of a story to track down news leaks and said that he would resign if the mayor asked him to. `` Whether or not I retain the public confidence ... is ... a matter for the public to decide, for the mayor to decide and for the school board to decide,'' <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON> said at a news conference Tuesday afternoon. <PERSON> Schmoke </PERSON> called <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON>' actions `` a terrible mistake in judgment.'' `` My view is that the public can tolerate an official being wrong on an issue,'' <PERSON> Schmoke </PERSON> said. `` What people generally find intolerable is an official lying to them.'' Tape recordings of <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON>'s remarks Monday to the <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, a political club, show he said he leaked false information to school board members `` to see if they were lying to me.'' `` I know who's doing the lying,'' he said in the speech. `` I know who it is. I feed them the lies, then they run out and lie to the press.'' <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON> said Tuesday he could not recall using the word `` lie'' in describing the way he released information on how candidates for school superintendent would be interviewed earlier this year. He said he believed leaks were undermining the selection process, because some candidates threatened to withdraw if their candidacies were made public. He said he had become a political target and the object of news leaks because of his attempts to uncover favoritism in the awarding of grants in the school system. Board member <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutman </PERSON> said Tuesday that he was bewildered by <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON>' remarks. `` I think there's something wrong with the man. I do n't even know what he's talking about,'' <PERSON> Gutman </PERSON> said. `` The whole thing is getting uglier and uglier. We are trustees -LRB- with -RRB- the most important responsibility in the city.'' Some board members, <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON> said, `` walk out of meetings and tell you we have a deal and then before I can get to my office the press is calling me asking me ` did you all decide so and so.' `` I know who they are. I know who is doing the leaking. I know who is doing the lying. That's OK. It will be taken care of in time,'' <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON> acknowledged dissension within the board. However, he took issue with an article in Monday's editions of The -LRB- <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> -RRB- Sun, which said the school board was in a revolt. Problems arose last spring between <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON> and board members when they were prevented from participating in the selection of a new school superintendent. Problems resurfaced in July when <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON> decided to hire a new executive director and several board members said they felt the full board should have voted on the post.
