<FIRST>r a PM-6Miles-FAARules     09-13 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-6 Miles-FAA Rules,0695</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Regulations Date Back to 1930s</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-6 Miles Up and Sleepy II</HEAD>
<HEAD>By FRED BAYLES</HEAD>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Today's federal rules for pilot rest and duty hours come out of the era of the DC-3, when propeller-driven airliners droned along at speeds less than 200 mph and took eight hours to fly from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. Revised in 1964 and again in 1985, many of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulations </ORGANIZATION> differ little from rules first issued in the 1930s. Crews for large airlines on domestic routes ca n't be scheduled to fly longer than eight hours between required rest periods. They ca n't fly more than 30 hours in seven days; 100 hours a month and 1,000 hours a year. Crews may exceed the eight-hour limit if their scheduled flights are delayed by weather, traffic or equipment problems. Commuter airline pilots may fly 34 hours in 7 days; 120 hours in a month and 1,200 a year. Crews must be given at least nine hours' rest in a 24-hour period. However, that can be cut to eight hours if the next rest period is increased by two to three hours, based on an <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> formula. Three-member international crews can fly up to 12 hours a day; they must get 18 hours' rest if they fly more than 24 hours in 72 hours or 20 hours within 48 hours. Larger crews can fly longer; two-member crews can fly only eight hours between rest periods. However, the rules do n't speak to duty hours _ measured from the time a pilot reports to the airport, usually an hour before first takeoff, through the day's schedule including sitting on the ground between flights, to departure after the final flight. Such reckoning can stretch a crew's time on the job to 16 hours. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> limit their pilots' hours by calculating duty time, the number of takeoffs and landings, the time of day and the number of time zones crossed None of these factors is considered under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commercial regulations. The latest <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> rules are the result of so-called `` regulation by negotiation.'' Union and airline representatives met in 1983-84 with <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials and a mediator to work out minor changes in domestic rules. These rules are often used by airlines and their unions as a baseline for schedules stricter than government guidelines. `` Our own rules go on beyond the FAR -LRB- federal air regulations -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Hof </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> flight operations. `` We find the FAR is a place to begin.'' <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> administrator <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> strongly denies federal regulations run second in safety to union contracts. `` Our standard is not the thinnest ice you can skate on,'' he said. Yet in 1975 an <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> investigation of a series of Pan American crashes in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> raised questions about the adequacy of <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> regulations. Dr. <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohler </PERSON>, then chief of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s Aeromedical Applications Division, suggested <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> regulators look to the factors that the Europeans use to set flying limits. `` It was the feeling at the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> to leave it up to the unions to negotiate relative to their airlines' specific type of flying,'' said <PERSON> Mohler </PERSON>, now head of aerospace medicine at <ORGANIZATION> Wright </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` It seemed to make sense, up until deregulation.'' With deregulation, airlines stretched into new markets, added new routes and faced new competition. Efforts to cut costs and keep fares low put pressure on various parts of the industry, including the pilots. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Airline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the average pilot flies 13 percent more each month today than 10 years ago. <PERSON> McArtor </PERSON> says he has an open mind to change. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> is supporting fatigue research being done by <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> on several airlines. `` I do n't know of any carrier that wo n't voluntarily do all they can to ensure efficiency in the cockpit,'' he said. `` But I do n't believe we know all that we will know about this phenomenon As we understand it better, the scheduling, I think, will reflect that.''
</TEXT>
