<HEAD>US Urged To Develop New Proposals On Arms Control</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should develop new proposals for U.S.-Soviet conventional arms control talks in case Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> succeeds in cutting back on military spending, says a key congressman. The plans should be prepared even though there's no indication <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has yet been successful, said Rep. <PERSON> Les </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Wis </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> `` A central element of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s ` new thinking' is that the Western threat can be reduced by political means _ that is, arms control _ which then reduces Soviet defense requirements,'' the report said. `` For <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, arms control can cut the size of the Western threat and a revised military doctrine can scale back the military's response to that threat,'' it said. The panel's defense policy subcommittee concluded Monday that `` to date, there have been no significant, identifiable changes traceable to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s drive to scale back defense spending.'' The study by the Democratic-run panel was based on a series of hearings, including testimony from the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, and other experts in government and private industry. Republican members of the panel issued a dissent, disputing the majority's implication that the Soviets may be moving away from what the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> legislators said is a drive to achieve nuclear superiority over the West. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has called for economic and military reforms aimed at shifting more spending into consumer goods and away from the huge Soviet military structure, <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> noted. `` <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reform agenda for the military is driven primarily by domestic concerns, not military or strategic factors,'' the study said. `` The equation is simple: In order for his economic reforms to succeed, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> must shift resources from the defense sector to civilian use.'' The current five-year plan began in 1986 and was developed before <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> took power in March 1985, <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said at a news conference. Some changes may be seen in the Soviets' next five-year plan, he said. `` There is a growing consensus among the experts that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> intends to shift some of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s economic capacity from military to civilian use,'' said <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON>. `` What the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> ought to be doing is probing. ... We should move cautiously and carefully, but we should move,'' he said. `` We need some concrete proposals in conventional arms.'' He was referring to the long-stalled talks aimed at reducing non-nuclear weapons and troops in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The upcoming `` year we're looking at is a critical year,'' <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said. `` It's too bad the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is in transition.'' As the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration winds down, no new proposals are likely. In addition, a new administration will take six to eight months to prepare its plans, no matter whether Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> or Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is elected president, <PERSON> Aspin </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials have a difficult time estimating Soviet military spending, since the Soviets do n't publish details about their programs. The Soviets appear to be spending about 18 percent of their gross national product on defense, compared to about 6 percent for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the study said. But the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> GNP is much larger. Soviet military spending increased about 2 percent annually in the decade before <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> took power, and has increased about 3 percent in each of the past two years. The study cited the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces -LRB- INF -RRB- treaty, which includes strict verification procedures and bigger cuts in the Soviet arsenal than in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stockpile of weapons. The <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> minority, led by Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ala </LOCATION>., the ranking Republican on the committee, criticized part of the report `` This report accepts, without the slightest qualification, the idea that the Soviet leadership has accepted the implications of nuclear parity _ implicitly meaning that the Soviets reject the concepts of superiority, pre-emption, first use and victory,'' the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> members said. `` The apparent justification underlying this assumption appears to be a decade of both Soviet public statements and arms control activities. However, neither can be taken at face value as evidence of a meaningful transformation in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear doctrine,'' the dissent said.
