<HEAD>Waiting For Help _ And For The Waters To Recede</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANCHHARAMPUR, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For the past two weeks, the 15,000 people of this town have been living in flood waters. They say they have received almost no help from the government, although the town is only 25 miles east of <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION>, the capital. Even in normal times, <PERSON> Banchharampur </PERSON> is isolated, like thousands of other towns and villages in this country that is now three-quarters submerged by overflowing rivers. There are no roads connecting the town to the outside world. The trip from <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> takes five hours by motorboat across winding rivers and through inundated rice paddies. Most people in <LOCATION> Banchharampur </LOCATION> are weavers or landless farmers who have not been able to work since the flood waters from the <LOCATION> Titash </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> reached their houses Aug. 29. <PERSON> Firoz </PERSON>, who delivers goods from the market when it is n't flooded, and his wife <PERSON> Hana </PERSON>, said they tried to get medical help for their 7-year-old daughter <PERSON> Rahima </PERSON>, who had a fever. `` Government medical workers came here once, but the crowd was too big and they left before we could see them,'' <PERSON> Firoz </PERSON> said. Townspeople said eight people drowned or died of diarrhea or dysentery caused by drinking contaminated water. He said his family had received 4.4 pounds of free rie from the government, and had to borrow money from other villagers to buy more. A grain seller named <PERSON> Farid </PERSON> said he had only two baskets of low-quality rice to sell. The government and foreign relief agencies are struggling to reach millions of marooned flood victims by helicopter and boat. But with at least 65,000 villages spread across 55,000 square miles _ an area the size of <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> _ the task is slow. On Sunday, fresh vegetables reached Banchharampur by boat from unsubmerged fields 12 miles away, but the prices had soared by as much as 175 percent since the floods began June 13. <PERSON> Sattar </PERSON>, his wife <PERSON> Alia </PERSON> and their three children normally eat 4.4 pounds of rice a day. Since the flood, the family has been getting by on 2.2 pounds or less of rice a day, <PERSON> Alia </PERSON> said. She uncovered a tin cooking pot, displaying an inch of rice in the bottom. `` This is all we have left. We have no more money,'' she said, speaking in Bengali through an interpreter. The family has purchased rice with <PERSON> Sattar </PERSON>'s last earnings as a porter, and money from the family's only salable item _ a chicken <PERSON> Alia </PERSON> managed to save when they abandoned their straw house, where the flood water has reached the roof. `` We stayed in our house until the water got as high as <PERSON> Saliha </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Alia </PERSON> said, drawing her oldest child close to her. <PERSON> Saliha </PERSON>, wearing only a pair of cotton shorts and a jewelry stud in her nostril, stood about three feet tall. <PERSON> Alia </PERSON> _ who like many Bangladeshis does n't have a family name _ said she did not know her daughter's age, but the girl appeared to be about 10. <PERSON> Alia </PERSON> said her family took refuge with 20 other people in one room of a hostel built for college students, where the water was 18 inches deep. The families piled wooden benches on top of each other in two tiers, creating a wobbly wooden platform above the water. The highest path through the village is a foot under water. Some people are living in houses where women wade waist-deep in water to cook food on boards propped just above the water. But life in the village went on. The government-run bank was open, although the few customers stood ankle-deep in water. At the deed registry office, clerks sat on platforms above the water with a black goat tethered in their midst.
</TEXT>
