<HEAD>Even Without Biaggi, Congressional Office Carries On</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> office for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s 19th Congressional District, phones still ring, mail comes in, letters go out. The only thing missing is a member of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Until Aug. 5, the district was represented by Rep. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, a Democrat who for nearly 20 years represented the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> and part of <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, who was convicted of racketeering last month in the <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> trial, resigned rather than face almost certain expulsion by his colleagues. But even without an elected representative, the work of the congressional office goes on. House rules provide for keeping offices running in the event that a member resigns, dies or is expelled. Constituents still get some services; what they do n't get is their own advocate who can sponsor and vote on legislation and perform work in committees. In the case of <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>'s constituents, they lost their voice in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last year when <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> agreed to stop voting on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor after being indicted for accepting illegal paid vacations. He later was convicted of that charge in a separate trial. Deputy Clerk <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Colley </PERSON> said that when a vacancy occurs in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, `` The clerk of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> becomes in effect the supervisor or manager of the vacant offices until a successor is elected.'' The clerk usually selects one of the former <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> member's senior staffers to run the office, <PERSON> Colley </PERSON> said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Blancato </PERSON>, <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>'s longtime administrative assistant, was appointed to run the office upon the congressman's departure. `` We are carrying on the way that not only <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> would expect of his staff and the years of experience that we have, but also using our own standards of what we believe we should do,'' <PERSON> Blancato </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Blancato </PERSON> said he still talks daily to <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, who has returned to the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION>, and that the business of the congressional office inevitably comes up. `` I do n't know if there are rules about discussing business,'' <PERSON> Blancato </PERSON> said. `` ... His advice and guidance and counsel, do I still need it for what I do everyday? Absolutely, sure.'' <PERSON> Colley </PERSON> said such communications are to be expected, and voiced confidence that <PERSON> Blancato </PERSON> `` understands his role and what he's doing. <PERSON> Blancato </PERSON> said he has no sense of role reversal during conversations with <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>. `` Every time I speak to him ... in a philosophical way, even if it is n't in a literal way, I'm stll speaking to my boss,'' he said. Even the hurdle of sponsoring legislation is not insurmountable without an elected representative. If the appointed administrator believes some problem requires legislation, `` He can talk to the other members of the delegation from that particular state and ask them to support the issue,'' <PERSON> Colley </PERSON> said. `` These are not unusual situations,'' <PERSON> Colley </PERSON> said. `` We have had vacancies for various reasons over the years.'' Ten seats, including one belonging to the delegate from <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Samoa </LOCATION>, have been vacated since the 100th <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> began almost two years ago, <PERSON> Colley </PERSON> said. Most of those seats have been filled through special elections. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> has called no special election to fill <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>'s seat, so whoever is elected on Nov. 8 wo n't begin serving until January 1989. Chances are good that <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> will be re-elected to the seat he vacated, but he has said he would not serve. If he wins, it is expected that he would quit again and a special election would be held.
