<HEAD>Inspector Says Rowan Violated Weapons Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A District of <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> police inspector testified that syndicated columnist <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> broke a local gun control law when he fired on a backyard intruder in June. Following a pre-trial hearing Monday that included testimony from police Inspector <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> D.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnett </PERSON> said he would rule by Friday on a motion that weapons charges against <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> be dismissed. <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON>, 63, has been charged with using an unregistered revolver to wound a teen-ager who was intruding in the backyard of his home. He also has been charged with unlawful possession of ammunition for the handgun. <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON>, who has written and spoken frequently on behalf of gun control, maintains that his son, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent, was told by city officials he was not required to register the weapon used in the June 14 shooting. <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> testified that he had complained repeatedly to police about trespassers and said that death threats heightened his concern over intruders. The columnist, who contends the police knew he had a gun, said he had warned a police officer that if anyone ever confronted him on his property late at night, he would have to shoot them and he did n't want to do that. The officer, <PERSON> Jasper </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chatman </PERSON>, contradicted <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON>'s testimony, saying, `` He never made a statement to me about any action he was going to take.'' <PERSON> Chatman </PERSON> said he'd been to the <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> house between 10 and 20 times in the last few years, all on complaints about trespassers using the pool. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, who has worked in the district's gun records division since 1976, said <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> had broken the law that prohibits anyone but the registered owner from using a weapon. He acknowledged that city police officers and federal law enforcement agents are not required to register weapons, but he insisted that only those individuals are allowed to use the weapons. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> added that it is a violation of law for other family members even to touch an agent's weapon. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> does not require agents to register with local authorities weapons used for official duties, according to <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> McElhaney </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. He declined to say whether a .22 - caliber revolver, the weapon used in the shooting, would normally be approved for use by <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a lawyer, testified Monday that he spoke three times with police about whether the weapon should be registered and was told he need n't register it, but never got a written statement on the matter. The senior <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> shot <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, 19, of suburban <LOCATION> Chevy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chase </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, on the night of June 14 after he caught <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> and three other youths taking an unauthorized swim in his pool. If convicted on the misdemeanor weapon and ammunition charges, <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> faces a possible maximum penalty of two years in prison and a $ 2,000 fine.
