<FIRST>r w PM-BurrowingNuke     09-13 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burrowing Nuke,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Pursues Development Of Earth-Burrowing Warheads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is pursuing the development of nuclear warheads that would penetrate the earth before detonating and which could be a more effective weapon against Soviet underground command centers. <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials said Monday that <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> had authorized development of the so-called `` burrowing nukes'' that have been under study for years. Military scientists are convinced they would be far more powerful against underground bunkers than other nuclear devices that explode on the surface, even if they do n't pack the same explosive power. The new weapon, which is highly classified and the responsibility of the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, is formally known as an earth penetrator. The Energy Department disclosed in June 1987 it had begun preliminary development work on the warhead needed for a burrowing missile because it expected the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> to request one. According to a <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman and other <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> sources, that request now has been formally made. The <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> will be expected to step up its work on warhead design while the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> pursues missile development and integration work. Spokeswoman <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bodyani </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acquisition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> last month recommended approval of an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> statement on the need for the weapon and <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> subsequently approved it. She said the final authorization was dated Aug. 19 `` and approves this program as a new start.'' She would not discuss program details such as funding and anticipated deployment schedules. Another Pentagon official, who insisted on anonymity, said <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> had directed the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> to provide cost estimates and predicted performance data for a more rudimentary version of the weapon that could be produced by modifying an existing missile or bomb. `` There will almost certainly be an interim earth penetrator,'' this official said. `` But the authorization clears the way for the broad-based research needed to produce a brand new weapon.'' The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration recently has begun spotlighting Soviet construction of underground bunkers, saying it appears the Russians are convinced they can protect their leaders while waging a nuclear war. Earlier this spring, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported in its latest edition of the publication `` Soviet Military Power'' that such construction had been under way for 40 years and the bunkers could `` accommodate thousands of people.'' A burrowing warhead would not have to penetrate more than a few feet before posing an increased threat to a bunker, but `` it's not easy'' to develop a warhead that can withstand the shock of striking and burrowing through the ground, one official said.
</TEXT>
