<FIRST>r w PM-LaunchDanger     09-13 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Launch Danger,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA, Air Force To Limit Journalists at Shuttle Launch Site</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: News conference scheduled for 2 p.m. EDT; top prospects
uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The viewing area from which reporters and spectators have watched 25 space shuttle launches at the Kennedy Space Center will be off-limits to most onlookers when shuttles start flying again because of safety concerns, officials say. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> on Monday announced the new precautions at the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, space facility, citing studies that `` have shown that the danger to persons on the ground is much greater than was understood should an accident occur.'' The restrictions cover the viewing area that overlooks launch complex 39, where space shuttle Discovery is being prepared for space. A press viewing area 3.5 miles from the launch pads has been used by media representatives since the shuttle program began. Invited guests, including astronauts' families, watched from a nearby VIP area, and Kennedy Space Center workers and their families also were able to watch from certain areas. Under the new plans, most nearby areas will be cleared just before and during the launch. Details of the plans were to be explained at a briefing today at the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> headquarters of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. The plan drew protests Monday from Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Fla </LOCATION>., who said at the Kennedy Space Center that the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION>, Space and Technology had argued against such a change in a letter sent Friday to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> `` I do n't think an iron curtain should be placed about the <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> when we're getting back into space,'' said <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, a member of the committee and chairman of its subcommittee on space science and applications. `` The press has been very much a part of the manned space flight program for 29 years and to arbitrarily say that some of that press has to be excluded is not right,'' <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> officials said the new rules were developed after studies of the Challenger explosion in January 1986 and the loss of an <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Titan 34D the following April. <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> range safety officers monitor each launch and have the responsibility of blowing up any rocket that strays out of control. During the Challenger accident, the solid-fueled rocket booster engines broke away and were destroyed by the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> range safety officer. A study of this accident, and of the Titan 34D loss, gave new understanding of the dangers to people near the launch pad, the announcement said. `` Under certain conditions, a solid rocket booster released from the vehicle as a result of an accident would follow an unknown ballistic trajectory rather than begin to tumble on course as had been previously thought,'' the announcement said. Also, the statement said, it was learned that if out-of-control boosters had to be destroyed in flight, `` the boosters fragmented into thousands of pieces and the explosive properties of unburned solid motor propellant were greater than originally determined in laboratory tests.'' `` Because of this new information,'' the statement said, `` <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> have determined that the prudent action is to minimize the population at the close-in viewing areas.'' Accredited journalists will be able to work in the area `` except for the hours just before the launch and the launch itself,'' the statement said. During the prohibited period, only `` media with an immediate need for the facilities at the press site will be allowed.'' The rest, it said, will view the launch from a site on a causeway. The alternate site will be equipped with a countdown clock, audio commentary and video monitors. About 3,000 members of the media have requested accreditation for the first post-Challenger launch, that of Discovery, which is expected to occur in about two weeks. The exact number that will be permitted at the press site has not been disclosed. The letter to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> from the congressional committee, headed by Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roe </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, said, in part, `` Although we have no doubt that the new assessments leading to this proposal are well intended, the calculation of such risks is highly uncertain.'' It asked the president to intercede and permit continued access to traditional viewing areas.
</TEXT>
