<HEAD>Authorities Censor Only TV Propaganda Allowed Pinochet Opponents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities banned a television broadcast by the opposition because it contained a report on torture of dissidents, political activists said. The banned 15-minute, late-night segment is the only televised political program allowed to opponents of President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, the sole candidate in a presidential referendum next month that could extend his rule for eight years. Also Monday, six people wounded during street violence Sunday were reported in serious condition with gunshot wounds. All were from <PERSON> Cerro </PERSON> <PERSON> Navia </PERSON>, a northwestern working-class suburb of <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>, where Gen. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s motorcade was stoned by angry protesters on Sunday's 15th anniversary of the military coup in which he seized power. National police responded by using tear gas and water cannon to disperse demonstrators who hurled stones and set up barricades of burning tires. About 50 people were wounded and 400 arrested, police said. The government-controlled <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> said the opposition program was rejected Monday night because `` it did not abide by the electoral law,'' which grants the government and opposition 15 minutes each of free time on national television to carry their message to voters in an Oct. 5 presidential referendum. The free nightly broadcasts, from 10:45 p.m. to 11:15 p.m., are the only television advertisements allowed to the opposition. The government has ample access to the television, which it controls. The programs started one week ago. A coalition of 16 parties opposing the re-election of <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> said the program was censored because it included an interview with a judge, <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, who told about the torture of political dissidents by security agents. `` We reject the attempt by government officials to determine what Chileans can and can not see on television,'' the coalition said in a statement. `` Our struggle in the upcoming referendum includes the promotion of a complete freedom of expresion and rejection of any kind of censorship.'' The government's 15-minute program was broadcast normally Monday night. In addition, the government has maintained for months a series of ads urging voters to support <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> in the referendum. The law prohibits political advertisement on television, but the government claims it is not breaking the law. It says its ads do not constitute `` political propaganda,'' but an information to citizens on its works and achievements. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> that censored the opposition program includes Education Minister <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Guzman </PERSON> and several other government officials. The council's secretary, <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lustig </PERSON>, appeared on state television to say that the opposition program was barred because the comments by Judge <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> had not been authorized by the court in which he serves. The opposition called the council's decision `` illegal and unconstitutional.'' <PERSON> Genaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Ariagada </PERSON>, secretary general of the opposition coalition, denied the censored program broke the law. `` The only one that has broken the law here is the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Arriagada </PERSON> said. `` This an abuse that every decent Chilean citizen must reject.'' When the time came for the opposition program to be broadcast, a sign appeared on the screen saying it had been suspended because it `` did not abide by the law.'' Within minutes, residents in a number of <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> neighborhoods started banging empty pots from inside their homes, a traditional form of protest. In the Oct. 5 referendum, voters will vote `` yes'' or `` no'' on <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, the single candidate nominated by the nation's military commanders, including <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> himself as commander of the army. About 7.2 million voters are registered for the Oct. 5 poll. If approved by voters, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> will start a new eight-year term next March. If rejected, an open election will be held within a year, with <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> remaining in power until then. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> toppled the elected government of President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON> and took power Sept. 11, 1973. <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, a Marxist, died in the takeover.
</TEXT>
