<HEAD>Britain Says Evidence Of Iraqi Chemical Weapon `Compelling'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The British government, citing evidence from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, pressed for a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> investigation of charges that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> used chemical weapons against ethnic Kurds. `` We now consider the weight of evidence of the use of chemical weapons to be compelling,'' said a <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> spokesman who, in accordance with British practice, demanded anonymity. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> asked <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary - General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> on Monday to send a team to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to investigate the allegations that poison gas was used against the Kurds, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported in today's editions In a story from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the newspaper cited unidentified diplomatic sources as saying the request from the four allies reflects a growing irritation with the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> government for ignoring <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> protests over prior use of chemical weapons during <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s 8-year war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The British <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said it toughened its stand Monday partly because of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> evidence of such attacks, which led the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Friday to vote for tough economic sanctions against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The measure sti