<FIRST>r a PM-Fires-Rebirth     09-13 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires-Rebirth,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yellowstone's Rebirth Already Under Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With Sierra Fire, Bjt
^By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAMMOTH HOT SPRINGS, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Blades of grass and wildflowers are sprouting through much of the blackened earth at <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>, heralding a dynamic rebirth in the wake of the fires, park researchers say. The vegetation was spotted around <LOCATION> Grant </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION>, which was besieged by flames last month, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Varley </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>'s chief of research In other areas of the park, scorched pine cones from lodgepole pines, <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>'s predominant conifer, are slowly opening to spill their seeds to the earth, he said Monday. However, it is hard to say how quickly the burned areas will rebound from the devastating summer of 1988, <PERSON> Varley </PERSON> said. In the 16 years since <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officials adopted a `` let-it-burn'' policy for most naturally caused fires, there have been approximately 140 wildfires in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> that seared some 33,000 acres, said the researcher. But those fires did n't fully prepare researchers for this summer's blazes, so predicting how the forests will rebound is not easy, he added `` We have a considerable body of knowledge on the rate at which these things recover,'' said <PERSON> Varley </PERSON>. `` We're pretty confident that they would come back well.'' To help make those projections, a team of scientists and researchers will meet next month to study the aftermath, <PERSON> Varley </PERSON> said. The fires have created a huge laboratory for <PERSON> Varley </PERSON> and his colleagues that will show them <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>'s regenerative capabilities. It also will show tourists the devastation of fires. `` It is not dead,'' stressed <PERSON> Varley </PERSON>. `` There are some tops of things that are certainly killed. But again, on the basis of the 16 years, that experience that we've had with fire and the research thereof, we know that there will be a lot of sprouting. We know that most of the living organisms are underneath the surface of the soil and still are alive and well.'' The grasses and flowers that have reappeared around <LOCATION> Grant </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Varley </PERSON>, have done so without rainfall. `` These plants are remarkably resilient to fire,'' he said. `` Most of the species have insurance policies, so to speak, because they've been putting up with fire for thousands of years. Some of the strategies are truly remarkable.'' One example, he said, is the lodgepole pine. Its cones are covered by resins that are melted away by fire, causing `` that cone to open up slowly after the fire passes.'' `` And so in many of these areas, in places that totally look like moonscapes, then these seeds are being broadcasted out over the forest floor right now, and that's the next generation that will be coming up,'' <PERSON> Varley </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
