<HEAD>Seoul Announces Breakthrough In Relations With Communist Bloc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government said today it has agreed with <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> to open permanent missions, the first diplomatic relations between <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and a communist nation. The move to normalize relations stopped short of full diplomatic recognition, but <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> officials said they expected the two nations to establish diplomatic ties in the near future. The <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> government is hoping the Olympic Games, which begin in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> on Saturday, will play a major role in helping to open relations with communist nations. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Choi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kwang-soo </PERSON> went on national television to announce the two governments had agreed to open missions in their capitals of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> to oversee trade, scientific and cultural relations and consular affairs. The two governments agreed to start negotiations on establishing full diplomatic relations, a ministry statement said. `` Both governments expressed their determination to bring their negotiations to a success as soon as possible,'' it said. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has no relations with communist nations because of its bitter rivalry with communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. The North has opposed any ties between communist nations and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON>, who took office in February, has worked to establish relations with communist nations to try to reduce tension with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and to boost trade. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> wants to establish relations with the North's main allies, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, to reduce their support for any <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> threat to the South. `` The exchange of missions is very significant in that <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has secured a bridgehead for <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s advance into the East European bloc,'' said a senior official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and most other communist nations ignored a North Korean call to boycott the Olympics. The <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> government hopes the participation of communist nations in the Olympics will play a major role in developing relations. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> said it will boycott the Olympics because its demand to be a co-host of the Games was turned down by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Olympic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on the grounds that they are awarded to a single city. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> invaded the South in 1950 and sparked the bloody, three-year Korean War. The two sides technically remain at war since no peace treaty was signed and the <PERSON> North </PERSON> has staged a series of attacks on the South over the years. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> agreed last year to establish trade offices in the first such move between <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and a communist nation. The <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> government is anxious to develop trade with communist nations to open new markets and reduce its dependence on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as its main export market.
