<HEAD>NRC: Management Ready to Operate Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Managers at <LOCATION> Pilgrim </LOCATION> nuclear power plant, shut down since 1986 under a government order, can handle a restart under careful supervision, federal regulators concluded. A Nuclear Regulatory Commission inspection at Pilgrim recently concluded `` with high confidence'' that <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> management controls, programs and personnel are ready to support safe startup and operation of the plant, an <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> official said Monday. The commission ordered the closing because of technical and management problems. An inspection conducted Aug. 8-24 found no `` fundamental flaws'' that would inhibit reactor or public safety during plant operation, said <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>'s deputy director of the reactor projects division. Inspectors reached their conclusions after carefully monitoring managers' performance and qualifications, said <PERSON> Collin </PERSON>. He said the problem of how to decide if managers could do a good job of running a nuclear power plant by judging their performance at an idled facility was partly solved by using a simulator. The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> is still evaluating whether the plant should be allowed to restart. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> noted that intense supervision would be necessary under actual operating conditions. `` We intend to stay very close to that station during any proposed restart program,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> has proposed a four-month supervisory plan for the restart process, said utility spokeswoman <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>. `` It's a very careful, well-considered approach to the restart process. There will be very intensive <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> oversight, but it also provides for additional senior management oversight,'' she said. The inspection consisted of interviews with licensee personnel, plant tours, observations of plant activities, and selective examinations of procedures, records and documents. Inspectors also observed plant activities on all shifts. Most of the senior management is new since 1986, but many department heads remained in place, Ms. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said. The previous management was often unstable, fixing a problem in one area but then neglecting to maintain the improvement, <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. `` The team they have now appears to be committed to the station and they have a pretty good track record in the industry,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said.
