 Soldiers who stormed a hijacked plane in <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> in March shot a passenger in the back and did n't take precautions to prevent injuring innocent people, a government newspaper reported. <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>'s article Monday represented a rare public criticism of the country's security forces, and raised new questions about the bungled attempt to end the March 8 hijacking. `` Our forces are not prepared to act in extreme situations,'' said an article published Monday in the state-run daily <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>. A family of 11 Siberian jazz musicians known as the Ovechkins hijacked a Tu-154 plane carrying 76 people on a flight from the Siberian city of <LOCATION> Irkutsk </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>. They demanded that the <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> Soviet jetliner fly to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Ground controllers tricked the family into thinking the plane was landing in <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, but it actually touched down at an airfield near <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>. A special anti-terrorist squad of soldiers stormed the plane after the Ovechkins set off a homemade bomb, starting a fire, Soviet press reports said. The soldiers killed a stewardess and three passengers in the amubush, during which four of the Ovechkins committed suicide after killing their mother at her request, the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported. In the disorderly evacuation of passengers, some were forced to jump onto the tarmac and 35 people were injured, news reports said. The Izvestia article, quoting witnesses who testifieed at the trial of two members of the <PERSON> Ovechkin </PERSON> family that began last week, called into question the assault squad's actions. `` I fell onto the ground, crouched, my hands were twisted behind me, I was placed with my face to the concrete and shot in the back,'' said a passenger identified only as <PERSON> Maizel </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> student. He implied that the soldiers mistook him for one of the hijackers. `` Then they ... moved me forward several meters -LRB- yards -RRB- and put my face down and made me lie with my arms behind my head,'' <PERSON> Maizel </PERSON> added. He said the soldiers beat him on his legs and tried to hit his face and head, but he shielded himself. The prosecutor's office is investigating this incident and other actions of the rescue squad. Two of the surviving Ovechkins, 28-year-old <PERSON> Olga </PERSON> and her 17-year-old brother, <PERSON> Igor </PERSON>, went on trial Sept. 6 in <LOCATION> Irkutsk </LOCATION>. They are charged with `` seizing an airliner with a view to flying abroad with use of arms that resulted in the death of people and other grave consequences,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. It said <PERSON> Olga </PERSON> <PERSON> Ovechkin </PERSON> testified that she tried to prevent her brothers from hijacking the plane.
