<HEAD>Residents Watch, Pack And Wait As Fire Creeps Closer</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Sierra Fire, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE WILDWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyer </PERSON> loaded her station wagon with family pictures and memorabilia and her husband, <PERSON> Bud </PERSON>, sprayed water on the dry grass around their home while a mountain blaze flickered just up the hillside. `` We stayed last night, and I want to stay, but a fire is one of the worst of my fears,'' she said late Monday night. At least 15 homes have been lost in the affluent residential area and the fire continued to burn on the edge of the community, about 60 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, on Monday evening. The out-of-control mountain blaze has forced the evacuation of at least 8,000 people. At least 142 structures, including nearly 100 homes, were destroyed, according to officials who early today estimated the blaze had burned more than 20,000 acres. Around the <PERSON> Boyers </PERSON>' home, separated by a 30-foot street and just one row of homes from the closest burning trees, about a third of the homes were still occupied by residents who said they would n't leave until the last moment But <PERSON> Boyer </PERSON>, 48, said one sleepless night was all he and his 46-year-old wife could take. `` We stayed last night, but we did n't sleep at all, did n't even try. We stayed with the house all day,'' he said. `` It seems the fire came up, backed down and now it's back up again, only closer.'' For <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Derrick </PERSON>, 64, and his wife, <PERSON> Jean </PERSON>, 63, the fire that brushed through this <LOCATION> Sierra </LOCATION> foothill community was a stunning shock, but not a new experience. `` I'm going to think positively. We went through it before and we will again,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Derrick </PERSON> said, recalling being evacuated from a 1971 fire that came near their home in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Chatsworth </LOCATION>. The Derricks moved into their new retirement home here just a month ago. `` I ca n't believe it,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Derrick </PERSON> said. `` I do n't even have the drapes up yet The paint is n't even dry. This is just terrible.'' For some residents, the fire made a quick entrance into their community. `` All of a sudden it was here,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bridges </PERSON>, 30. `` It swept right past us, even burned the brush under the deck, but the house did n't catch. I ca n't image all the things we would have lost,'' he said. Bridges and a friend, <PERSON> Matt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldrom </PERSON>, 28, said after the fire brushed past Bridges' home Sunday night they joined about six other residents to help three professional firefighters. `` I could n't believe those guys,'' <PERSON> Waldrom </PERSON> said. `` They told us exactly what to do and we saved maybe a half dozen homes, and they told us, ` Watch out. It's coming.''' `` It was half a mile away, and two minutes later it was 100 yards away, and we got behind a building and it blew right by us. I've never seen anything like it.'' `` It was terrible,'' Bridges added, `` but it was probably the most satisfying weekend of my life. We saved some homes, and I even saved my brand new truck.''
