 <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> officials are still uncertain about what caused Flight 225 to skid off a runway and its nose gear to collapse, the second such accident in recent months involving a DC-10's landing gear. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> said there were 197 passengers and 10 crew members on board the flight, which originated in <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, and made stops in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. No one was seriously injured. The nose gear broke when the plane went off the runway during landing at <LOCATION> Stapleton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> at 1:50 p.m. In May, the nose gear on an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> DC-10 collapsed when it ran off the end of a runway at <LOCATION> Dallas-Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. Six people were injured in that accident, which prompted a special <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> investigation of all DC-10 landing gear braking systems. That investigation is incomplete. In Monday's accident, a pilot said he lost control of the steering on the 13-year-old plane just as it landed, said Lt. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Stout </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Denver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> officials declined to speculate on the cause. Many passengers were shaken after the rough landing _ one passenger suffered a minor ankle injury during the evacuation _ but they praised the actions of the crew. `` People were really flipping out, but the -LRB- flight attendants -RRB- were incredibly under control,'' said passenger <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lampe </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo </LOCATION><LOCATION> . </LOCATION> The Rev. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Loebl </PERSON>, a Jesuit priest from <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, said the plane landed `` on a wing and a prayer.'' `` I was afraid, but all God needs is a good simple act of trust and he can do the rest,'' he said. `` And there were a lot of people besides me praying.'' `` When we got on the bus to take us back to the terminal, we all cheered,'' <PERSON> Loebl </PERSON> said. `` Once for the crew, because they were great, and once just because we made it.'' Passenger <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Bandt </PERSON> said she knows what caused the accident. `` The plane got sick,'' said the 3-year-old, who had bumps and scrapes like many of the other passengers.
