<HEAD>Reagan Signing Anti-Discrimination Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The White House is turning on some election-year, Rose Garden charm to celebrate President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s signing of a bill that strengthens the government's power to combat housing discrimination Some 100 congressional leaders, Cabinet officers and other administration officials were scheduled to gather today at the White House to witness the presidential signing ceremony. The effort is seen as a boon to the White House aspirations of Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, whose staff was described as helping forge a compromise on the measure. But members of both parties, however, had rushed to become co-sponsors of the measure after the president signaled his willingness to sign it into law. The original fair housing law, passed in 1968 after the assassination of <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, gave the federal government only a mediation role in settling housing disputes. Under the new law, the secretary of housing and urban development is empowered to go to court to seek stiff fines against property owners accused of discrimination. The bill received final congressional approval in early August, before <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> left on his traditional three-week summer vacation. However, the legislation's transfer to the White House was delayed so that a signing ceremony could be held after <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s return to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> last week. The measure gives the federal government its first significant powers to combate housing discrimination. The handicapped and families with children under 18 would be protected for the first time from housing discrimination. The current law covered discrimination against racial minorities and legislation signed into law in 1974 barred discrimination on the basis of sex. Sen. <PERSON> Arlen </PERSON> <PERSON> Specter </PERSON>, R-Pa., a chief sponsor, hailed the new legislation as giving the government `` a tough remedy'' against housing discrimination Specter credited <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s staff with being `` very active'' in negotiating compromise language that helped bring the bill to the floor. Other primary sponsors of the bill included Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., and Rep. <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> Fish, <LOCATION> R-N </LOCATION> Opponents of the measure, such as Sen. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Symms </PERSON>, R-Idaho., had criticized the measure as `` unfair housing bill,'' contending it intruded on property rights and increased costs due to accessibility requirements for the handicapped and disabled Other major provisions of the bill include: _ The secretary of housing and urban development would try to win a conciliation agreement after a complaint is filed If that effort fails, the secretary or any party could take the case to an independent administrative law judge in <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> or to <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. _ If the administrative judge finds that someone has engaged or is about to engage in a discriminatory practice, he shall order appropriate relief, which may include actual damages, an injunction or civil penalties _ The maximum fines would be $ 10,000 for a first violation, $ 25,000 for a second violation in a five-year period and $ 50,000 for two or more violations within a seven-year period _ New buildings with four or more units must be constructed to they are readily accessible to the handicapped Doors must be wide enough to accommodate wheelchairs; switches and outlets must be in accessible locations; bathroom walls must be reinforced to allow later installation of grab bars. This would apply to dwellings set for occupancy 30 months after the law's enactment. _ Children could be barred from housing intended for the elderly Such housing is defined as a community where at least 80 percent of the dwellings are occupied by at least one person age 55 or older, and significant facilities and services are provided; or those occupied solely by people age 62 and older.
</TEXT>
