<HEAD>Soviet Leader Gets Second Day Of Complaints From Siberians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For the second day in a row, Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> faced complaints today from Siberians angry about housing, food shortages and medical care. After <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told workers at a synthetic fiber factory that the ruling Politburo he heads was asked to turn special attention to a shortage of kindergartens, a voice rang out: `` We have kindergartens. We do n't have housing, and the medical facilities are bad,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency quoted one worker as shouting to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> at the <LOCATION> Khimvolokno </LOCATION> plant in the Siberian city of <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION>. On Monday, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> heard similar complaints when he stopped in a tiny village, <LOCATION> Yemelyanovo </LOCATION>, on his way to <LOCATION> Kransoyarsk </LOCATION> from the airport to which he had flown from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` We have no hot water. You do what you can to wash,'' one man shouted at the 57-year-old Communist Party chief. Usually, Soviet citizens politely praise <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his policies or ask mild questions when he stops for chats as he tours the vast country. But <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> came back from a six-week vacation to a street-side discussion in <LOCATION> Yemelyanovo </LOCATION> and at the <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> factory filled with complaints about food and living conditions. The evening television news program Vremya led its Monday evening program with a report of about 20 minutes on <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s trip to the city about 2,000 miles east of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> It included the acrimonious exchange in <LOCATION> Yemeleyanovo </LOCATION>. As a crowd pressed closer and closer to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON>, shouting complaints and questions, the general secretary cut in: `` OK, comrades, I got caught your drift.'' The Soviet leader blamed local and national officials for failing to develop social services in <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION>, and reiterated that he is committed to providing each Soviet family with a separate apartment by the year 2000. But some in the crowd were not satisfied. `` There will never be that,'' said one man, apparently referring to the planned individual housing. Another man doubted the discussion would be covered by the officially controlled media. `` <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Sergeyevich </PERSON>, will everything be shown on television or will half be cut out?'' `` All of it will be shown,'' the Soviet leader responded. One of the most vocal of the crowd members, a blond-haired man in his 20s, began the complaints by shouting about poor management of a local grain storage facility. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> asked for support for his reform policies as residents complained about long lines for meat, sausage and other foods, as well as a lack of hot water. `` The most important thing is that you believe in our politics and in the leadership that is still being formed. It's still being formed at the regional and provincial levels,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. He told the group that he was not interested in blind faith, but in reasoned trust for his policies and the people implementing them. `` We're on the right path, comrades,'' he said. `` No need to get lost. We're on the right path.'' Today, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> stopped at <LOCATION> Khimvolokno </LOCATION>, which <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said was a factory key to improving the supply and quality of consumer goods. The plant is now under reconstruction because it, as well as associated facilities, are old. `` Social development has chronically lagged: housing, schools and hospitals. Now we must together restore that which we lost during those long years,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> as saying. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> would stay in the <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> region, which occupies one-tenth of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, until the end of the week. <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> also is the site of a Soviet radar station that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> says is an obstacle to arms control negotiations. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> did not discuss the radar site in comments distributed by the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency and shown on Soviet television. He had been out of public view since July 30, when he met with the West German foreign minister. Soviet officials said he had been on vacation.
