 <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> today called for an <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> investigation of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s alleged use of chemical weapons against ethnic Kurds. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> joined the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> call, asking the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to send a team to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to look into allegations that gas was used against the Kurds, most of whom live in northern <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and eastern <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Okun </PERSON>, the second-ranking diplomat at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Mission to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, met Monday with Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> to make the request, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> said today in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Okun </PERSON> acted on behalf of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, said the spokeswoman, who requested anonymity. <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` is extremely concerned about chemical warfare'' and backed a recent unanimous resolution by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION