the past.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> `` is on a magical mystery tour,'' promising to create a fund to rebuild <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> with a helping hand from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. But the vice president said this helping hand is reaching right for the voters' wallets. `` What will pay for that helping hand? Your money. And who is being helped? Not you,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` This is n't a helping hand,'' he said. `` This is the same old heavy hand of government.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> set the tone for today's speech during appearances SMonday at a Hispanic-owned food plant in <LOCATION> Secaucus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, and a rally at an <LOCATION> Alton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, shopping center. Touring the <ORGANIZATION> Goya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> plant, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told 100 employees that Hispanic workers `` have been some of the biggest winners in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s economic comeback,'' with their jobs increasing at three times the rate of the entire <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> labor force. At the shopping center, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> attacked the Democratic presidential nominee for suggesting that the vice president was emulating the late <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, the inquisitorial anti-communist senator who questioned the patriotism of many Americans in the 1950s. At the same time, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> suggested that he was a friend of the people and implied that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was n't. `` He suggested that when I said he's a card-carrying member of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, that that was McCarthyism,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told a crowd of about 7,000 supporters. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> actually used 