<HEAD>Postal Employees Return To Work After Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Postal employees began returning to work today after nearly two weeks of strikes, but officials said it would take as many weeks to deliver a backlog of 150 million letters and packages. The strike ended Monday night after the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> reached an agreement with post office officials. The two sides said they established a framework for further talks on differences over pay bonuses, overtime compensation and the hiring of temporary staff. The union, which represents the 140,000 post office employees involved in the dispute, said it hoped all workers would be back at work by Thursday. About 1,700 workers returned to post offices by mid-morning today while more than 98,000 other strikers continued negotiations, <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> said. She said workers are on their jobs at <LOCATION> Tonbridge </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sevenoaks </LOCATION>, both southeast of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, and in other small offices around the country. Public mailboxes that were sealed during the dispute will be opened gradually, she said. Post office officials said international mail and first-class letters and parcels will receive priority as the backlog of mail is cleared over the next two weeks. About half of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s 1,500 post offices were closed during the strike, and only one of the 82 major mail sorting centers _ in <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> _ remained open during the strike. <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> said the agreement condones the `` use of temporary staff, reasonable levels of overtime -LRB- pay -RRB- ... and some diversions of mail to offices which can best handle it.'' The post office wants to pay bonuses to new workers i