<HEAD>Survey: 30 Percent of Top Teens Have Considered Suicide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Story had been embargoed until Wednesday. The embargo has
been broken.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Teen Stress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thirty percent of high-achieving teen-agers said they have considered committing suicide and 45 percent said they knew someone who had killed themself or had tried to, a new survey found. The 19th annual survey of high achievers, conducted by polling teen-agers listed in the directory `` Who's <ORGANIZATION> Who </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Among </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION>,'' found that 4 percent said they had tried to commit suicide. Since the survey began tracking attitudes toward suicide among high achievers four years ago, the percentage who reported knowing a teen-ager who had attempted or committed suicide has grown from 40 percent to 45 percent. The percentage who reported having personally considered suicide has been relatively stable, rising from 28 percent to 30 percent over the four-year period, while the percentage who report trying to commit suicide went from 3 percent to 4 percent, the organization said. `` The problem may be especially serious among black high achievers,'' the organization said in a news release. The survey found that 10 percent of the black high-achievers polled this year said they had attempted suicide. The survey results were based on responses from 2,024 students, 5 percent of whom were black, the Who's Who organization said. On other issues, the new Who's Who survey found that drug use continues dropping among the nation's brightest high school students, with less than 1 percent reporting they smoke marijuana more than once a month. That's down from 4 percent five years ago and 11 percent a decade ago. Alcohol use also is decreasing, with 63 percent of the teen-agers surveyed saying they never drink alcohol, compared to 50 percent in 1978 and 48 percent in 1983. The news release did not contain a margin of error for the survey, and Who's Who officials cautioned that it was not designed to be representative of all teens. `` It's important to note these statistics represent high achievers, not the general teen population,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Krouse </PERSON>, publisher of the directory of high school students. He noted that the findings on suicide were lower than those found in the recent survey by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Physical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, Recreation and Dance, which polled a general teen-age sample.
</TEXT>
