<HEAD>Opposition Rejects Government-Run Elections</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 16 grafs to UPDATE with hunger strike and details
of meeting between opposition and election commission. PICKS up 9th
graf, `Gen. Saw ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Opposition leaders today rejected elections that would be organized by the country's one-party government and repeated their call for an interim government to supervise the vote. About 75 students and others, including two <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks, went on a 48-hour fast for democracy, reviving a tactic used decades ago in the struggle for greater freedom from British colonial rule. Tens of thousands of people marched in the capital demanding the interim government. They included striking government employees, uniformed students and about 3,000 uniformed doctors, nurses and staff members of militry and other hospitals. The demonstrations were smaller than those the day before. After weeks of political turmoil, many people in this city of 3.5 million have begun eating rice porridge or gruel instead of pure rice because prices have skyrocketed due to growing shortages. Strikes by transportation workers and a lack of fuel have restricted supplies from the countryside, and there has been hoarding by worried residents. A 4.4-pound bag of rice that cost the equivalent of $ 1.70 a month ago now costs $ 5.80. Gasoline was selling at $ 16 a gallon on the black market, compared to $ 1 a year ago, a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat said. Opposition leaders <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> and former Defense Minister Tin Oo said in their meeting with the government-appointed election commission that they will not support or take part in the elections and will continue pressing for an interim government. The <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which came to power in a 1962 military coup, announced Saturday it will end 26 years of one-party rule and hold elections as early as the end of October. They told the commission that polling could not be conducted in the country's rapidly deteriorating security situation, <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON> said later. <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON> said he told election commission chairman <PERSON> Ba </PERSON> <PERSON> Htay </PERSON>, a retired financial commissioner under a pre-1962 civilian government: `` After 26 years of this rule, most people in the country do not know you and will not have confidence. More so, people do not trust any government-appointed commission.'' Like the other four elderly commission members, <PERSON> Ba </PERSON> <PERSON> Htay </PERSON> is regarded as politically neutral. The three opposition leaders were later joined by a fourth anti-government figure, former Prime Minister Nu, in a meeting with student rebel leaders. The students asked them to immediately form an interim government, but were told that was not possible without cooperation from the current government. On Monday, <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON>, and Tin Oo signed their first joint statement, a letter to President <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> demanding the interim government. Photographs of them eating together and signing the statement received prominent display in private and government-run newspapers Tuesday, buoying the opposition movement. This morning, the group of hunger strikers sat on the road in front of City Hall, where several anti-government demonstrators were shot dead by security forces Aug. 8. They began fasting at 9 a.m., looked after by doctors and other sympathizers. Gen. <PERSON> Saw </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>, defense minister and armed forces chief of staff, called for citizens and the military to cooperate in holding the proposed government-organized general elections. The last multi-party elections in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> were held Feb. 6, 1960, when former Prime Minister Nu's <ORGANIZATION> Clean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anti-Fascist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> won a landslide victory over an army-backed party. Gen. Ne Win led the March 1962 coup that toppled Nu, who uses only one name. The military crushed dissent and pursued rigid policies that made <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>, once one of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s richest countries, one of the world's poorest nations. In September 1987, students stages riots against the government's economic policies, followed by widespread protests in March and in June. After Ne Win resigned July 23, the party chose hardliner <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> to succeed him. After only 17 days in office, <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> was succeded on Aug. 19 by <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>, the first civilian leader since Nu.
