<SECOND>PM-Peruvian Tomb,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rich Cache Of Gold, Art Found In Ancient Peruvian Tomb</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 1,500-year-old tomb uncovered on the northern coast of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> has yielded one of the richest collections of crafted gold and artifacts ever found in the <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geographic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> announced today. The tomb, officials said, was the burial place for a warrior-priest of the Moche people, a civilization that dominated the Peruvian area from 100 A.D. to about the end of the 7th century. `` This is the richest tomb ever excavated archaeologically in the western hemisphere,'' according to <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Donnan </PERSON>, an expert on ancient <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Alva </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Bruning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Archaeological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lambayeque </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, said that the area near the village of <LOCATION> Sipan </LOCATION> may be the burial site for a succession of high-ranking Moche leaders and that other tombs with more treasure may be found. `` I am sure that when we finish digging here, we will know more about the life, social and economic organization, the metallurgical knowledge and religious practices of the Moche,'' <PERSON> Alva </PERSON> was quoted as saying in an announcement released by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geographic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. Officials said the Moche peoples dominated the Peruvian area prior to the time of the Inca civilization. The <ORGANIZATION> Incas </ORGANIZATION> were the most powerful group in the area at the time of the Spanish conquest in the 1530s. The Moche tomb was discovered after authorities learned in January 1987, that a number of remarkably fine gold and silver artifacts were being sold on the black market in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>. Police raided the home of a tomb robber and, after a shoot out that killed one person, recovered some of the treasures. Information gathered from the raid led to the <LOCATION> Sipan </LOCATION> area and the tomb was found after careful excavation. Among the treasures found were a crown, mask, knives and jewelry of gold, along with more than 1,000 ceramic and copper artifacts. In addition to the warrior-priest, the tomb also contained the remains of two women and three other men, all apparently part of a ceremonial entombment ritual. Excavation of the tomb was financed by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geographic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> under the auspices of the Peruvian government.
