ame type of financial crisis,'' he said. The Bakkers and <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON> were not in court Monday or today, but <PERSON> Hovis </PERSON> told reporters he plans to call them as witnesses when it is time to present their case. Meanwhile, bankruptcy trustee M.C. `` Red'' <PERSON> Benton </PERSON> filed papers in court saying he could n't meet Monday's deadline to recommend a buyer for the ministry's assets. He asked for an extension until Sept. 27 to continue negotiations. In court Monday, <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> lawyers maintained that the <ORGANIZATION> Bakkers </ORGANIZATION> took huge personal bonuses while bills were n't being paid, and used money that was raised to build hotels as general operating funds. Entered into court records were numerous memos from <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> to <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> recommending such things as cutting expenses, reducing payroll and using competitive bidding for construction jobs. <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> said some staff members were hesitant to approach <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> with information about financial problems. `` He -LRB- <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> -RRB- was out there planning and building, and he had a saying _ he did n't want to hear any bad news,'' <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> lawyers used internal documents to detail the ministry's problems from 1984-1987 They cited bonuses given to the <ORGANIZATION> Bakkers </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Taggart </PERSON> at the same time the ministry was having serious financial problems.
