<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A third of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> adults questioned in a recent survey said they personally know a teen-ager who either committed suicide or tried to, according to a report released today. A separate study of high-achieving teen-agers, meanwhile, disclosed that 30 percent said they have considered suicide and 45 percent know someone who has tried it, or succeeded. The national survey of 1,000 adults, questioned by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Private </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospitals </ORGANIZATION>, found that 27 percent of those questioned said they knew a teen-ager who had tried to kill themselves and 17 percent knew a teen-ager who had killed themselves. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Riter </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Riter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Annapolis </LOCATION>, Md. company that conducted the survey, said there was overlapping and that a net of 32 percent of those questioned knew a teen-ager in one of the two categories. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Meeks </PERSON>, a child psychiatrist and a professor at <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said the study was `` reassuring'' in the sense it showed adults realize that modern teen-agers face severe problems. `` Teen-agers frequently worry that adults do n't take their problems seriously,'' <PERSON> Meeks </PERSON> said at a news conference. Entitled `` Teen-agers at Risk: an Adult Perspective,'' the survey also found that 72.4 percent of those interviewed think teen-agers today face far more serious problems than they did at the same age. The survey commissioned by the Washington-based organization also found that adults focused on three major areas of concern when asked about 10 specific problems facing adolescents: drug abuse, alcohol abuse and peer pressure. Slightly more than 87 percent said drug abuse was an `` overwhelming'' concern, alcohol abuse was second and peer pressure third. Unwanted pregnancy ranked fourth with 70.8 percent. A cluster appeared around the next five areas: Child abuse, 56 percent; crime among teen-agers, 54 percent; depression 53 percent; conflict with parents 53 percent; and suicide 53 percent. The 10th greatest concern was runaway behavior at 44.5 percent. Notwithstanding the concern expressed for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s youth, 47 percent of those questioned agreed that when a teen-ager is admitted to a psychiatric hospital `` it puts a cloud over this person's head for the rest of his @ her life.'' And 86.3 percent agreed to some degree that `` families find it difficult to admit that their children need professional psychiatric help.'' Of those questioned, 17.1 percent had teen-age children and 31.5 percent had children under 12. Grandparents represented 30.7 percent of the sample. The survey of high-achieving teen-agers was conducted by polling youths listed in the directory `` Who's <ORGANIZATION> Who </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Among </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION>.'' Four percent of the 2,024 respondents said they had actually attempted suicide. It was the fourth year for that study. During that period the share who said they knew someone who has tried suicide rose from 40 percent to 45 percent; those considering it were up from 28 percent to 30 percent, and those who tried edged up from 3 percent to 4 percent.
