acre park since June. About 1,000 Marines from <LOCATION> Camp </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pendleton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, were to reach <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> today to bolster firefighters. Some of the first soldiers sent to <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> troops from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lewis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, were not to be released until at least Saturday. `` We'll have lots of people here, so maybe we can nail this thing,'' <PERSON> Bungarz </PERSON> said. Firefighters worked Monday to strengthen fire lines and attack hot spots as officials worked to establish a fire camp at Mammoth Hot Springs. The favorable weather allowed park officials to open all roads through the park except the northeast entrance leading to <LOCATION> Cooke </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, where workers were repairing roads. Despite the return of warmer weather, the arrival of fall, with lower temperatures and shorter days, had officials optimistic the fires would make no more major advances. `` We still expect fire activity, but it wo n't be as intense or as much or as fast as it has been in the past,'' said fire information officer <PERSON> Sonya </PERSON> <PERSON> Capek </PERSON>. `` The days are getting shorter, so the burning period is getting shorter.'' Officials were also hopeful that a heavy snow will throw a wet, white blanket on the fires soon. Light snow fell on Yellowstone Sunday. `` We can generally expect some pretty good snowfalls in September and early October,'' said the park's chief researcher, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Varley </PERSON>. `` We usually have a pretty good snowstorm around the equinox -LRB- Sept. 21 -RRB-, and I think we've all got our fingers crossed that that will indeed come and put a further damper on the fires.'' Elsewhere in the <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> area, firefighte