<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A firebombing apparently stemming from a $ 275 drug deal that went sour killed two young sisters who had been left alone in a locked room and critically injured a third, police said. The Sunday evening firebombing had been meant for another man in the building, authorities said. Police announced today that they have arrested one man and were expecting the surrender of a second later in the day. Lt. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollocher </PERSON> said investigators were seeking warrants charging both with two counts of first-degree murder, arson and assault. Their identities were not released pending formal filing of charges. Four men who had been with the suspects were being sought for questioning. Sgt. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcinkiewicz </PERSON> of the bomb and arson squad said investigators had determined that two Molotov cocktails were thrown through a first-floor window of the three-story home. Firefighters rescued the children, who authorities said had been left unattended in a locked bedroom. But <PERSON> Erica </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, 1, and <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, 4, died later of smoke inhalation at Children's Hospital <PERSON> Lenora </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, 5 months, was in critical condition this morning, a hospital spokeswoman said. The children's mother, <PERSON> Cassandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, 18, was not at home at the time of the firebombing because she and her boyfriend were out looking for her 16-year-old brother, who was allegedly involved in the drug deal, <PERSON> Marcinkiewicz </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Marcinkiewicz </PERSON> said that shortly after 11 p.m. Sunday, six men stopped at the home and one of them paid $ 275 for drugs to the brother and another 16-year-olds. Instead of giving the man drugs, the two youths fled with the money, the investigator said. He said the car returned about 20 minutes later, and the firebombs were hurled into the house. Several