<HEAD>California Supreme Court Upholds LA Closure Of Gay Bathhouse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: note content 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has refused to hear the appeal of a gay bathhouse that was shut down by a court order under a new <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> enforcement policy aimed at combatting the spread of AIDS. The court's action Monday left intact the first such order under the county's policy, which requires any bathhouse in which anal or oral sex takes place to be closed as a public nuisance. A previous policy prohibited anal sex without condoms in bathhouses but did not seek to close the establishments. `` We were attempting to work with bathhouses, have them serve as education centers,'' said Deputy County Counsel <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Carnevale </PERSON>. `` We thought they would go away by themselves because they were losing business. It turned out that they were much larger than anybody expected.'' Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is spread largely through sexual contact and sharing of infected needles by drug abusers. In May, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> officials sought to close <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION>'s bathhouse after an undercover investigation found numerous violations An injunction was issued Aug. 30. After a state appeals court refused to intervene, lawyers for <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION>'s appealed last week to the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Attorney <PERSON> Barrett </PERSON> <PERSON> Litt </PERSON> argued that the order closing Mac's was excessive because an order forbidding specific sexual practices would accomplish the same goal while protecting the privacy rights of the bathhouse's customers. Quoting a number of health experts, <PERSON> Litt </PERSON> said closing gay bathhouses would not reduce the risk of AIDS and would likely increase it. Sexual activities at bathhouses were `` safer than in the general population,'' he said. After the violations were found, Mac's required every patron to sign a copy of the rules, distributed cards stating the risk of specific types of sexual activities, and started showing `` safe sex'' videos, <PERSON> Litt </PERSON> said. The county still has about 10 bathhouses, which are generally making good-faith efforts to follow the rules prohibiting sexual intercourse, <PERSON> Carnevale </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> closed down its gay bathhouses.
