<TEXT>
 Heavy combat in northern rebel strongholds killed or wounded more than 80 leftists guerrillas and government troops, a military spokesman said today. Col. <PERSON> Galileo </PERSON> <PERSON> Torres </PERSON> said guerrillas attacked the <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paraiso </LOCATION> garrison, headquarters of the 4th army brigade, in <LOCATION> Chalatenango </LOCATION> province at 1:05 a.m. with mortar fire. Nine soldiers and five guerrillas died in the attack 37 miles north of the capital of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and 12 government troops were wounded, he said. <PERSON> Torres </PERSON>, head of the armed forces press office, also said there were a series of clashes in northern <LOCATION> Morazan </LOCATION> province between government units and guerrillas. The rebels suffered 50 casualties in <LOCATION> Morazan </LOCATION> and five soldiers were wounded, he said in a telephone interview. Both provinces are strongholds of the rebel <ORGANIZATION> Faribuno </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> where guerrillas move freely and even exercise some administration of towns and villages. He said the fighting at <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paraiso </LOCATION> lasted two hours and officers on the scene believed `` quite a few'' rebels were wounded. The bodies of five rebels and six M-16 assault rifles were recovered, <PERSON> Torres </PERSON> said. It was the first guerrilla attack on a brigade headquarters since a February assault on the 3rd brigade in eastern <LOCATION> Usulutan </LOCATION> province. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military adviser, the first to die in combat, was killed at <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paraiso </LOCATION> in March 1987 when rebels penetrated the base, killing 70 government soldiers. There are several dozen <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military advisers at bases in <LOCATION> Chalatenango </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Torres </PERSON> said the fighting in <LOCATION> Morazan </LOCATION> began at 4 p.m. Monday and lasted until 3 a.m. Tuesday. He called it a series of encounters between three government commando units of about 15 men each and a `` significant'' guerrilla column. Helicopters ferrying wounded soldiers and supplies were still coming under fire several hours after the main clashes ended, he said, and troops were still mopping up around <LOCATION> Gigante </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> outside <LOCATION> Perquin </LOCATION>, 125 miles northeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. He said Col. <PERSON> Emilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON>, commander of the eastern military zone, told him at mid-morning there was still no breakdown between dead and wounded in the 50 guerrilla casualities. He said he did not know how many bodies had been recovered. There was no way to immediately confirm the official casualty figures. Earlier this month, the military claimed 25 rebels dead near <LOCATION> Tejutepeque </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. But reporters at the scene confirmed only four dead. Precise casualties are also hard to pin down because the rebels try to remove their dead from the battlefield.
