<HEAD>City Ordered To Return Documents From Wayne Williams Files To FBI</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of documents relating to the slayings of 29 black children in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> must be returned to the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>, a judge has ruled. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> instructed city officials to return files containing 2,300 documents related to the investigation of the killings in 1979-81. The files were released to the public in 1987 along with <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> police files on the case. The federal government then sued <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> Public Safety Commissioner <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Napper </PERSON>, charging that he violated federal law when he released <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> documents along with the police files. <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>'s order, filed Aug. 31, said the issue was whether the city had acted properly in releasing information the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> had shared only on the condition it remain confidential. `` The court here is not concerned with whether the investigatory documents should be released to the public,'' <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>'s order said. `` The question before the court is who owns, and is entitled to possession of, the documents.'' <PERSON> Napper </PERSON> had released the police files in response to an order by <ORGANIZATION> Fulton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> Alverson </PERSON>, who ruled in a lawsuit filed by several news media organizations. <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> free-lance photographer, was convicted in 1982 of two of the 29 murders and was sentenced to life imprisonment. Police officials later attributed 22 other slayings to <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>; five cases remain open. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> is appealing his conviction.
