<HEAD>Pentagon Cuts Length of Panama Duty Tours</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has ordered a cut in the required tour length for all military personnel stationed in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> as part of an effort to reduce the number of dependents in the troubled Central American nation, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>, the department's chief spokesman, said the policy change would reduce from 36 months to 30 months the required tour for servicemen accompanied by their families and drop from 24 months to 15 months the tour for those deploying alone. The latter reduction is considered the most important. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> explained the department also is enforcing a change to its `` concurrent travel'' policy, under which servicemen can not bring their families to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> unless they have already secured housing on a military reservation. Since there is currently a waiting period of up to nine months for such housing, `` the new tour length should encourage more soldiers just to go unaccompanied,'' added Maj. <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> is the home of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, the organization responsible for all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military forces in Central and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. About 10,000 American servicemen are stationed permanently in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, and about 2,200 others have been assigned there on a temporary basis since the spring to upgrade security at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases. According to <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, the decision to reduce the tour lengths was made initially last week by the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, gaining the approval of Gen. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vuono </PERSON>, the chief of staff, and <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsh </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> then reviewed the matter and ordered similar changes for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, which have much smaller contingents in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. Over the past six months, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> has succeeded in reducing by 50 percent the number of military families living outside <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bases in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> _ dropping the total still off base to about 1,100. The effort has taken on more momentum this summer because of what the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> describes as a deliberate campaign of harassing Americans assigned to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> said on Aug. 21 that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> personnel had reported at least 240 incidents of harassment by Panamanian authorities this year, including attempts to extort bribes for traffic violations and the stoppage of mail. The harassment comes at a time when the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is continuing to press economic sanctions against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> in a bid to oust the country's military leader, Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who has been indicted by two federal grand juries in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> on drug-trafficking charges.
