er </PERSON>, 20, another Mormon missionary who was on his way to <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION> to take up a post there. One of the injured passengers, <PERSON> Cruz </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> Albuquerque </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> that after the impact he hit the floor while others were thrown around the bus. He said he saw a crying infant trapped beneath some seats; the child's mother, who appeared to be dead, was nearby. `` Children were crying, people were crying, people were lying down,'' <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> said. He said he and another man freed the infant and then began helping other passengers from the bus because they feared an explosion. `` I feel fortunate,'' he said. `` I did n't even feel the pain until afterwards. ... I was just concerned for that woman and her baby.'' <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> said the driver was `` taking it easy,'' going only 45 or 55 mph, when the crash occurred. The 14 injured were taken to the emergency room of <LOCATION> Espanola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, nearly 20 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Embudo </LOCATION>, said hospital administrator <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>. He said four people were admitted, two of whom were later transferred to another hospital, and 10 were treated for lesser injuries and released. <PERSON> Vicki </PERSON> <PERSON> Dudley </PERSON>, district sales manager for Greyhound in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, who was at the scene, said the company is cooperating with the police and rescue investigation but declined to comment further.
