<HEAD>Vermont Leads Unemployment List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> has slipped from first place to 10th in the past year among states with the lowest unemployment rates, while neighboring <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> emerged as the best job provider for its residents, according to a government report issued Tuesday. With an unemployment rate of just 2.3 percent in July, and just 6,900 of its workers lacking jobs, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> replaced <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> as the state with the lowest joblessness, the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, whose jobless rate climbed from 2 percent in June to 2.5 percent in July, had been leading the nation with the lowest unemployment since last October. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' unemployment rate, meanwhile, rose from 3.4 percent in June to 3.6 percent in July. It was a full percentage point higher that the same month a year ago, when it held the title as the state with the lowest joblessness. The number of jobless in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> climbed by more than 25,000 to 155,600 over the year, despite the addition of nearly 60,000 new jobs in the state, according to the <ORGANIZATION> BLS </ORGANIZATION> data. Following <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> with the lowest unemployment rates in July were <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> at 3.1 percent each, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> at 3.2 percent each, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> at 3.3 percent, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> at 3.4 percent and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> at 3.5 percent. <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> continued to be the only state with double-digit joblessness, 10.2 percent in July, down from 10.6 percent a month earlier. <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> all had unemployment rates above 8 percent compared with a nationwide jobless rate of 5.5 percent for the month, the bureau said. All of the figures are unadjusted for seasonal variations. While the jobless rate nationwide declined 0.6 percentage point over the year, it dropped much more dramatically in several states. <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> all saw their unemployment rates drop by more than 2 full percentage points in the 12 months. Unemployment rates over the year rose in only three states: <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>. States with the largest job growth over the year were <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, up 6.1 percent; <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, up 5 percent; <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, both up 4.7 percent, and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, up 4.4 percent. The bureau said service type employment increased in virtually all of the states while 80 percent of them also showed gains in manufacturing, transportation, trade and government jobs. Cities with the lowest jobless rate in the country were <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vt. </LOCATION>, at 1.8 percent and <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, at 2 percent. <LOCATION> Flint </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, had the highest unemployment rate at 14.9 percent followed by the McAllen-Edinburg-Mission area of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> at 14.8 percent.
