<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said Tuesday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has `` compelling'' evidence that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has used chemical weapons against its Kurdish citizens. But he said the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> should conduct its own probe before being asked to condemn <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> for alleged genocide. Several members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said, however, that an immediate <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> session is imperative to make the case against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> contended that it is important that the world body investigate the facts independently. `` Not everybody agrees with what we say the facts are,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told the committee. He added that the government of <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> has said it can find no evidence among the Kurdish refugees fleeing from <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> that chemical weapons were used against them. `` What you want is for the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to form a team and go an see what the facts are,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> commented as senator after senator said the evidence the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> possesses appears to be solid and should be presented to the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> now, to bring into focus the question of whether <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> is subjecting its Kurdish minority to a deliberate campaign of genocide. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> reached the conclusion <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> is usi