<HEAD>House Passes Bill Protecting Aviation Workers Who Report Safety
Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed legislation Tuesday barring airlines, aircraft manufacturers and other aviation companies from retaliating against employees who complain to the government about safety problems. The measure prohibits employers from firing or taking other actions against workers who notify government agencies about what they believe are safety problems, or who refuse to allow an aircraft to operate because they believe a hazardous condition exists. The bill, passed on a voice vote, gained momentum this year after lawmakers heard from workers, including pilots and other employees of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, who complained that pressure was placed by management on those who object to safety problems. `` It is imperative employees feel they can come to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> or to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> with their safety concerns so the traveling public can be protected,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> The bill's future is uncertain because there is no similar <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> version. There is a much broader <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> measure that would protect all private-sector whistleblowers, including aviation industry workers, but that bill seems unlikely to pass this year. The House bill would allow workers to appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> if they believe they have lost their jobs or been punished because they complained about safety problems. A party dissatisfied with the labor secretary's decision could appeal to an administrative law judge within the department, and ultimately to the courts. If a worker is found to have brought his complaint in bad faith, the employee can be held liable for the company's legal fees, up to $ 5,000.
