<TEXT>
 The British <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> is hoping the Boy Scouts and the local <ORGANIZATION> PTO </ORGANIZATION> can help them out. The <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> wants to take back from the town a bell that once rang aboard the destroyer HMS <LOCATION> Campbeltown </LOCATION>. The bell was one of 50 returned to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> after World War II. All were taken from the 50 <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> destroyers given to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION> under a lend-lease program in 1940. The <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> plans to commission a new HMS <LOCATION> Campbeltown </LOCATION> in March and would like the original bell. British officials have offered a replica. Members of the <ORGANIZATION> Campbelltown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the bell's caretaker, said the town should decide. At a meeting Monday night, the fire company put the issue to a committee of representatives from the Boy Scouts, the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Londonderry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Township </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legion </ORGANIZATION>, the fire company, fire company auxiliary, <ORGANIZATION> Parent-Teacher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Campbelltown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and a justice of the peace. The new committee will be asked to decide if the issue should be put to a town vote.
