<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gratkowski </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Easthampton </LOCATION> soon will be turning heads when he drives by. He has <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' commercial license plate No. 1. <PERSON> Gratkowski </PERSON> won the tags in a special lottery held Tuesday at the Registry of Motor Vehicles headquarters, but was not present when his entry was drawn. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> distributes two license plates to drivers. His application was picked in a ceremony that has become commonplace since Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> ordered the lottery to put an end to cronyism in the distribution of low-number plates, both commercial and passenger. In the latest drawing, the registry had 14 low-number plates available and received 1,500 eligible entries. The entries were placed in the same drum used by the state Lottery.
