<HEAD>Children And Monks Join Protests For Democracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Burma-Army, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Children and monks joined thousands of striking civil servants who marched through <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> on Tuesday to demand the government resign and be replaced by an interim administration to supervise multiparty elections. Opposition leaders told a new Parliament-appointed election commission that neither they nor the people will accept elections organized by the government. International telephone and telex lines from <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> were cut off Tuesday, but it was not known if they were deliberately disrupted, since communications with <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> normally are poor. Residents of the capital were hoarding food and cutting down on rice consumption as transportation strikes pushed up the prices of essential items. About 75 people _ including two <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks _ began a two-day pro-democracy hunger strike outside city hall. On Monday, more than 1,000 children ending a 36-hour fast gathered at the <ORGANIZATION> Rangoon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> shouting `` Give Us Democracy!'' and `` Give Us Interim Government!'' Tens of thousands of striking government workers, students, medical personnel, children and monks staged peaceful demonstrations in <LOCATION> Rangoon </LOCATION> Tuesday against President <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> and his ruling <ORGANIZATION> Burma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Opposition leaders <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> San </PERSON> <PERSON> Suu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kyi </PERSON> and former Defense Minister Tin Oo told the election commission they rejected the government's promise to end 26 years of one-party rule and hold elections as early as late October. The three told the commission that polling could not be held amidst the country's political turmoil and violence, <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON> said, and that they will not support or participate in elections organized by the government. In a letter to <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> on Monday, the opposition demanded an interim government. The three leaders also said it would be unfair to hold the elections before opposition groups form parties and raise funds to compete against ruling party candidates, state-run <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rangoon </ORGANIZATION> reported. <PERSON> Aung </PERSON> <PERSON> Gyi </PERSON> said he told election commission chairman <PERSON> Ba </PERSON> <PERSON> Htay </PERSON>, a retired financial commissioner under a pre-1962 civilian government: `` I know you and I respect your integrity and I am confident you want to hold a free and fair election, but after 26 years of this rule, most people in the country do not know you and will not have confidence. More so, people do not trust any government-appointed commission.'' Like the other four elderly commission members, <PERSON> Ba </PERSON> <PERSON> Htay </PERSON> is regarded as politically neutral. In this city of 3.5 million, strikes by transportation workers and a lack of fuel have restricted food deliveries from the countryside. The resulting shortages and an increase in the price of staples such as rice have forced residents to eat porridge or gruel and to hoard food. A 4.4-pound bag of rice that cost $ 1.70 a month ago now costs $ 5.80, said a <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity. He said gasoline was selling for $ 16 a gallon on the black market, compared to $ 1 a year ago. The last multiparty elections in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> were held Feb. 6, 1960, when former Prime Minister U Nu's <ORGANIZATION> Clean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anti-Fascist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> won a landslide victory over an army-backed party Gen. Ne Win led the March 1962 coup that toppled U Nu. The military crushed dissent and pursued rigid policies that made <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>, once one of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s richest countries, one of the world's poorest nations In September 1987, students staged riots against the government's economic policies, followed by widespread protests in March and in June. After Ne Win resigned July 23, the party chose hardliner <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> to succeed him. After only 17 days in office and massive anti-government protests, <PERSON> Sein </PERSON> <PERSON> Lwin </PERSON> was replaced on Aug. 19 by <PERSON> Maung </PERSON> <PERSON> Maung </PERSON>, the first civilian leader since U Nu.
