<HEAD>Nautilus Inventor Loses Suit Against `20-20'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 2nd to UPDATE with Jones comment.
Deletes now-outdated last 2 grafs.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has thrown out a $ 4 billion libel lawsuit brought by the inventor of the Nautilus exercise machine, who claimed he was defamed in a `` 20-20'' news program. Nothing in the episode damaged <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' reputation, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Kovachevich </PERSON> said in a ruling last week. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said Tuesday from his ranch near <LOCATION> Ocala </LOCATION> that his attorney would appeal. `` I'm not happy with the judge's ruling ... in a case where we're patently right and they're patently wrong,'' he said. `` We'll take it clear to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> if we have to. The broadcast concerned <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' attempts to save 63 baby West African elephants by flying them from <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> to his ranch. The elephants had been slated for slaughter to control the size of the herd. In 1984, `` 20-20'' broadcast a segment about <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' efforts to save the animals. In a March 1987 follow-up, the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> show revealed some elephants were being sold from <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' ranch. Reporter <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Caras </PERSON> said several elephants had gone to small circuses, `` a fate worse than death.'' In an on-air exchange with anchor <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON>, <PERSON> Caras </PERSON> said <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> should have kept the elephants for good, as had been implied from the beginning. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> was quoted as saying that he did not have control of the animals at the time they were being sold because he was selling business assets. But the company buying the assets told <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> it was not responsible for selling the elephants. Two weeks after the segment aired, <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> sued, saying the show deliberately made him seem dishonest and cruel. `` The court finds that a reasonable person would not have intrepreted the broadcast, in whole or in part, as being defamatory,'' Ms. <PERSON> Kovachevich </PERSON> wrote. She found that the statements in the broadcast were either constitutionally protected opinion or not damaging to <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' reputation.
