<FIRST>r w AM-MentalIllness     09-13 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mental Illness,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Those Most Mentally Ill Get Worst Care, Groups Contend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The most seriously mentally ill patients in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> tend to get the worst treatment largely because so many good psychiatrists leave public hospitals to make more money in private practice, two advocacy groups contended Tuesday. `` The lack of adequate services for the seriously mentally ill is the major failure of American medicine and social services,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> for the Mentally Ill said in a report. Dr. <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>, co-founder with <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> group </ORGANIZATION>, called for `` using the leverage of federal funding to force'' psychiatrists to devote a certain amount of time to working in public mental health facilities. At a news conference and in a subsequent interview, <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> said medical schools in general are more heavily subsidized by federal money than other professional schools and that psychiatric training is the most heavily subsidized of the medical specialities. `` It's almost impossible to get competent psychiatrists in public practice in some states,'' said <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> <PERSON> Torrey </PERSON>, a psychiatrist and a co-author of the report. He said it would not be too much to require psychiatrists to devote four or five hours a month to public practice in return for having their education subsidized by tax money. The report itself said the failure to provide adequate care `` is particularly striking since we now know that the majority of these people can be successfully treated and rehabilitated.'' Expanding on a ranking system first used in 1986, a new survey by the groups concluded that <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> are the best at providing services. Lowest-rated in the survey were <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Torrey </PERSON> said being at the top of the list was not much to crow about. `` When most are giving third - and fourth-class care, states that are delivering second-class care look pretty good It's a little like being the smartest kid in the dumb class at school,'' he said The report said: `` In general, it can be said that hospital care for the seriously mentally ill in state mental hospitals is somewhat worse than it was two years ago, while outpatient services are modestly better. `` Rehabilitation services and housing for the seriously mentally ill remain on the best of days seriously deficient and on the worst of days abysmal,'' it said. `` The reasons for the general deterioration of hospital care center primarily on staffing deficiencies, especially in nursing and psychiatry,'' the report said. `` In both cases, the deficiencies are being exacerbated by the mushrooming of private psychiatric hospitals which are taking the best staff from the public sector with the lure of higher wages.'' It attributed marginal improvement in outpatient services `` to increased public attention to the sorry plight of the homeless mentally ill, an issue which has moved from the back alleys and grates of the city to the front pages of its newspapers.'' The report said conservative estimates suggest that nearly 2 million people in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are seriously mentally ill, with 8 percent of them hospitalized. `` Approximately one-third of homeless individuals are seriously mentally ill,'' the report said. `` Their visibility on <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s streets is a poignant reminder of the debacle of deinstitutionalization and failure of federally funded community mental health centers. <PERSON> Laurie </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> for the Mentally Ill, noted that her organization is made up of 70,000 families of people suffering from mental illness. `` For us the lack of services is a personal and family tragedy,'' she said. The overall state rankings were based on a composite figure drawn by awarding points ranging from zero to five in each of four categories: hospital care, outpatient services, rehabilitation and housing. The report relied on questionnaires to state mental health directors, various government surveys and visits to 35 states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. The report said 82 percent of the state mental health directors returned nine-page questionnaires _ when guaranteed anonymity _ even though their national organization did not endorse the survey.
</TEXT>
