<HEAD>State-By-State Rankings on Care for Mentally Ill</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mental Illness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are state-by-state rankings on the level of care provided for the seriously mentally ill as compiled by <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> for the Mentally Ill. The rankings were based on a composite figure drawn by assigning a zero to five-point value in each of four categories: hospital care, outpatient services, rehabilitation and housing. Data collection methods included questionnaires to state mental health directors and others, various government surveys and visits to 35 states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. When states have an equal number of points, they were ranked according to per capita income, with poor states ranked higher on the assumption that, all other things being equal, wealthy states should do better than poorer states. The number in brackets is the 1986 ranking. The groups said inclusion of additional data in the 1988 figures could account for some changes in position rather than actual improvement or worsening of services.
</TEXT>
