<FIRST>u w PM-MedicaidAbortions     09-13 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medicaid Abortions,350</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, bowing to a veto threat and the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s will, today retreated from its position that the federal Medicaid program should fund abortions for poor victims of rape and incest. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 47-43 to drop an amendment that would have liberalized the current policy of federal funds only when abortion is necessary to save a woman's life. In July, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 73-19 to expand Medicaid to pay for abortions in promptly reported cases of rape or incest. States would have had the option of retaining the current, more limited policy. The abortion controversy had been holding up a massive $ 140 billion spending bill meant to keep the departments of <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, and Education in business during fiscal 1989, which starts Oct. 1. The bill contains money for college loans, disadvantaged children, job training and AIDS research and education, among other things. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has repeatedly said he would veto the entire Labor-HHS-Education appropriations bill if it came to him with the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> abortion provision. The latest threat came in a letter Sept. 7 to congressional leaders. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Friday refused 216-166 to go along with the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> expansion. Three hours of often emotional debate preceded today's vote, with some senators decrying abortion and others maintaining that poor women in desperate circumstances deserve access to a legal medical option. `` The question is, is a child conceived by rape any less of a human being than one who is not?'' said Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION> `` One atrocity ... does n't justify another. Rape does n't justify murder.'' Sen. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON>, R-Conn., countered that it `` defies all common sense'' not to permit federal payments for `` the most narrow exceptions under the most extraordinary and dismal of circumstances. Fourteen states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> pay for Medicaid abortions, but only receive federal reimbursement for life-threatening cases. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote in July was the first time since 1981 that either chamber had approved more liberal eligibility.
</TEXT>
