<FIRST>r w AM-HousePledge     09-13 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House Pledge,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Opens Session With Pledge Of Allegiance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>, trying to juggle a political hot potato, broke with tradition Tuesday by opening its session with recitation of the Pledge of Allegiance. Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said the pledge, which has become an item of controversy in the presidential campaign, would be recited on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor at the beginning of each day's session until <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> adjourns next month. But <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, also lashed out harshly at Republicans who have sought to make the pledge an issue, saying such efforts are `` childish, immature and mean-spirited as a person can be.'' Rep. G.V. `` Sonny'' <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, D-Miss., held his hand over his heart as he led about three dozen lawmakers in reciting the 31-word pledge <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>'s podium was turned sideways from its normal position so he could see the large <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag that hangs behind the speaker's chair. The pledge was to be led on Wednesday by Rep. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, R-Calif., with Democrats and Republicans alternating days through the end of the session The members in the chamber Tuesday appeared to be roughly equally divided between the two parties. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Conn </LOCATION>., who brought the pledge squabble to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> chamber last week, called it a historic moment and said he would press to make the recitation a daily fixture <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> promised that such a rules change would be considered through normal channels. `` I compliment the speaker for recognizing that the dignity and integrity of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> would be enhanced by the recitation of the Pledge of Allegiance at the beginning of each session day,'' <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON> said. The pledge has become the centerpiece of an argument, begun in the presidential campaign, over whether Democrats or Republicans are more patriotic. Republican nominee <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> began the fight by criticizing Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for vetoing a bill in 1977 that would have penalized teachers for not leading the pledge in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> schools. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the governor, said he vetoed the bill because it was unconstitutional, and has labeled <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s attack a McCarthyite tactic. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> also repeated his belief that attempting to use the pledge as a political weapon `` is McCarthyism,'' a reference to the fervently anti-communist senator who impugned many Americans' patriotism in the 1950s The pledge, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said, is like the daily prayer that opens <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> sessions. `` It's a personal matter'' and members are `` free not to do so'' if they choose. `` I do n't think it's up to me to go around and see whose lips are moving,'' he said. Republicans appeared to delight last week when <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON> surprised the chamber's <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leadership and sought a sudden rules change to make the pledge permanent. The move was defeated on a 226-168 vote, largely along party lines. Without mentioning <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> today said `` the idea of trying to use the pledge as a wedge of division among Americans is what I regard as McCarthyism.'' He added: `` To suggest that another political party is less patriotic ... is childish, immature and mean-spirited as a person can be.'' <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON> rose after the pledge was recited today to add that he agreed with <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> that it should `` not be confrontational.'' <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> formally endorsed the pledge in a 1942 law, and the words `` under God'' were added in 1954 by a second law. But the 31-word sentence has not been a part of the chamber's own routine.
