<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>'s campaigns for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have been pretty dull affairs the last couple of decades; he's won every one by a landslide. This year, <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> hopes for something new. He hopes to lose. At least he says he hopes to lose. Nothing comes at face value in <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> politics, a world where tempers run hot, bad blood runs deep and rap sheets serve as the nearest thing to a score card. What is certain is that the race for <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>'s seat is one of the oddest in years, even by <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> standards. A month ago, convicted of corruption, <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> quit his office. Now, he just might win it back. `` What we've got there are pretty unique circumstances,'' said <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Smock </PERSON>, historian of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>. Without checking, he said, the last case of an unwilling winner to spring to mind occurred in 1788. Of course, <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> has yet to win, and his opponents in the Democratic primary predict he wo n't. `` People have a lot of affection for him,'' said state <PERSON> Assemblyman </PERSON> <PERSON> Eliot </PERSON> <PERSON> Engel </PERSON>. `` But they're not going to vote for him.'' Some will. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>'s focus on constituent services made him immensely popular in his district, which takes in much of the north <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>. He won each of his last six races with at least 90 percent of the vote. Indeed, his career came to an end at the jury box rather than the ballot box. Twice in the past year he was convicted of federal corruption charges, and he was facing expulsion from the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> when he tearfully quit last month. In addition to resigning his seat, `` I am withdra