<HEAD>Appellate Court Hears Arguments Over Fairness Doctrine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An appellate court heard arguments Tuesday that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> decision to abolish the fairness doctrine for broadcasters both hurt and advanced the cause of free speech. The requirement that television and radio stations present opposing viewpoints on controversial questions was a `` prevalent deterrent to broadcasters to air public issues,'' FCC general counsel <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Killory </PERSON> told a panel of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here. `` Elimination of the doctrine would best further the public's interest in recieving robust debate on controversial issues,'' she told the three-judge panel, which is reviewing last year's 4-0 <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> vote abolishing the fairness standard The FCC found that because there were so many sources of information, the 38-year-old fairness doctrine was no longer needed to ensure the dissemination of all points of view in the debate on a public issue, she said. Enforcement of the fairness doctrine prompted many broadcasters to avoid controversial issues so they would not be required to air all sides to a question and the result was bland speech, she said. But <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartzman </PERSON>, executive director of the Media Access Project, accused the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> of ignoring abundant evidence that many broadcast outlets had not presented alternate points of view on controversial subjects. `` There was a blatant predisposition to reach this result, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> has flip-flopped,'' he told <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judges </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patricia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wald </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>. `` Why should n't an agency that now says we're concerned about core First Amendment values get credit for that?'' <PERSON> Starr </PERSON> asked. `` It's one thing for the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> to say it's sensitive to First Amendment concerns,'' <PERSON> Schwartzman </PERSON> said. But he accused the agency of conducting a `` one-sided and narrow review.'' If it found that the regulation had a chilling effect on free speech, `` the commission is free to tinker with the adminstration of the fairness doctrine,'' he said. `` It's very convenient outcome for the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> to say ` there is a very chilling effect, we have to throw out the whole thing.''' But <PERSON> Killory </PERSON> argued that stricter enforcment `` would require the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> to get into the editorial judgment of broadcasters.'' The fairness doctrine requires broadcast stations to present the opposing viewpoint on a controversial issue in the event that the other side had purchased advertising to promote its arguments. The doctrine's constitutionality was upheld by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1969, but in 1984 the high court said it would review that decision if presented with new evidence that enforcement was no longer necessary. The next year, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> concluded the doctrine no longer served the public interest but said it would continue its enforcement because of uncertainty over whetherit was legally binding. In 1986, the federal appeals court here found that the fairness doctrine was not codified as part of the 1959 Communications Act. <ORGANIZATION> Meredith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> then challenged the constitutionality of the fairness doctrine after the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> found that a station it owned in <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, had filed to present opposing views about the construction of a nuclear power plant. The appeals court ordered the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> to consider <PERSON> Meredith </PERSON>'s constitutional challenge, a review that resulted in the Aug. 4, 1987 vote to abolish the doctrine <PERSON> Floyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON>, a prominent First Amendment lawyer who represents <PERSON> Meredith </PERSON>, urged the panel to `` defer to old-fashioned commission expertise'' which found that `` the public is receiving information not because of the fairness doctrine but in spite of the fairness doctrine.'' Communications attorney <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyk </PERSON> predicted `` the case will turn on a constitutional issue. I think this is a case for the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>.'' Organizations supporting the CC included the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Reporters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> for the Freedom of the Press and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>.
