<HEAD>Cuba Says Envoy Fired At Stalking CIA Man</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Cuban Embassy charged Tuesday that its commercial attache, who was expelled along with the ambassador, opened fire on a <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> operative who had tried to get him to defect. The commercial attache, Third Secretary <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Medina </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, and the ambassador, <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez-Mell </PERSON>, left <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Tuesday on a scheduled flight for <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, en route to the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> capital, <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>. In a statement read on the embassy steps, First Secretary <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Armas </PERSON> charged that the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> operative was a former <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> diplomat who defected in June _ <PERSON> Florentino </PERSON> <PERSON> Azpillaga </PERSON> <PERSON> Lombard </PERSON>. De Armas claimed <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> secret services had worked together during the incident. The British Foreign Office was enraged by the shooting because of its strict ban on diplomats carrying arms. `` The traitor in a menacing way instructed <PERSON> Senor </PERSON> <PERSON> Medina </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> to defect,'' said <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Armas </PERSON>. `` In reply to this he took out the gun he was carrying, fired it and the group ran away.'' <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> police said in a statement that anti-terrorist squad detectives `` traced and interviewed'' a man slighted injured in the Monday afternoon shooting and `` we are wholly satisfied he was not posing a threat to anyone.'' `` We will not be releasing his details,'' the statement from <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> Yard police headquarters added. `` Following the action of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the inquiry is now closed.'' Officials at <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> Yard refused to elaborate. The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> told ambassador Fernandez-Mell he must take responsibility for <PERSON> Medina </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> being armed, but the ambassador told reporters at the airport that he found his swift ousting `` very strange.'' The British domestic new agency, <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said police sources confirmed that the wounded man `` was a security officer'' and part of a team keeping the diplomat under surveillance. Witnesses have said that <PERSON> Medina </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, who opened fire outside his apartment in west <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, shot at a group of three men and a woman who fled in a car. He was stopped by police, claimed diplomatic immunity and then told the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> he fired because he was in fear of his life. The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> refused to comment on the reports that the communist diplomat was under <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> security surveillance. `` We have reacted appropriately to a totally unacceptable and outrageous action on the streets of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>,'' said a spokesman, who according to British civil service practice, declined to be identified. <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> Radio, in a broadcast monitored in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Aspillaga </PERSON> defected from the Cuban Embassy in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, in June 1987 `` to put himself at the service of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATI