<HEAD>Pennsylvania Officials To Certify Radon Testers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, where the seriousness of radon contamination first came to light when a man set off radiation alarms at a nuclear plant, the state is moving to regulate companies that test homes for the deadly gas. The steps are the outgrowth of nearly four years experience with radon, an odorless, colorless gas the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has now linked to 20,000 lung cancer deaths a year nationwide. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said Monday every home in the country should be tested for radon because contamination is wider spread than previously believed. Radon is a radioactive gas, trace amounts of which are produced in the decay of uranium in soil and rocks. The gas is present in the outdoors normally at about 0.5 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s 4 picocurie `` action level.'' Homes tend to concentrate radon indoors. Radon kills people by leaving its radioactive decay products in the lungs, irradiating the tissues for a lifetime. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> will require companies testing for the gas to pass a state-approved course in radon detection, demonstrate at least a year of professional experience and agree to provide radon-testing data to the government, said <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaertner </PERSON>, a state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> official. After Sept. 21, `` it will be illegal to provide radon services in the state unless they are certified,'' he said Tuesday. `` It's simply a health issue which needs to be investigated house by house,'' <PERSON> Gaertner </PERSON> said. `` The problem levels are sprodadic, but in being sporadic, they're spread across the entire country. There are n't really bad areas, there are problem homes.'' <PERSON> Gaertner </PERSON>, who works in the DER's <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radiation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION>, said his office received `` a tremendous number'' of calls Tuesday because of the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> report. `` What we are really telling them is the same message we have been giving the public for a year now,'' <PERSON> Gaertner </PERSON> said. `` That message, based on DER data from the past, is that problem homes can occur anywhere in the state, but most people after testing do n't have a problem. In neighboring <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, the state <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said it had received more than 50 calls by mid-day Tuesday from residents concerned about the effects of radon gas. `` What the people are mainly concerned about is how they can get the radon kits to have their homes tested,'' said <PERSON> Rod </PERSON> <PERSON> Kovack </PERSON>, a radiological technician for the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` We've been furnishing them with a list of places where they can obtain the kits and along with that list, we've sent a couple of pamphlets that the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has put out for concerned homeowners.'' The <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> department plans to publish guidelines for contractors and homeowners on specific remediation techniques for homes with unacceptable radon levels, <PERSON> Gaertner </PERSON> said. A companion booklet will offer tips on selecting contractors, along with a list of state-certified contractors, he said. `` This will help the public in that the industry will be regulated,'' he said. `` We have n't seen severe problems, but you want to make sure problems do n't occur, that the firms have proper training and that they are following the proper methods for remediation.'' Of the 429 <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> homes tested in the national survey released Monday, 37 percent had more than 4 picocuries of radioactivity per liter of air, the level used by the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> as the trigger for more sophisticated tests that determine if remediation is needed. The highest level was 114 in <LOCATION> Perry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Those readings contrast to levels in the thousands of picocuries found previously in the uranium-rich Reading Prong geological formation of eastern <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gaertner </PERSON> said. Those earlier findings were accurate but rare, he said. `` What it did was present a distorted picture of the radon situation,'' he said. `` The highest reading we have encountered outside the Reading Prong is no more than 800. And now, we do a statistically random study and the highest reading is 114.'' On Dec. 14, 1984, <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Watras </PERSON>, a field engineer for a subcontractor building <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Limerick </LOCATION> nuclear plant, tripped radiation alarms as he went to work. Investigators discovered his home atop the Reading Prong had radon levels 675 times the acceptable state guidelines. He and his family were evacuated. The discovery awoke scientists and officials to the severity of radon contamination in some areas and led to the creation of the radiation bureau in <LOCATION> Gilbertsville </LOCATION>, about a two miles from <PERSON> Watras </PERSON>' home
</TEXT>
