<HEAD>Senate Drops Effort to Fund Abortions for Rape, Incest Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> surrendered to political reality Tuesday and gave up its fight to permit federally funded abortions for poor victims of rape and incest. Facing strong House opposition, a White House veto threat and the prospect of a $ 140 billion social spending bill held hostage to the abortion controversy, the chamber agreed by voice vote to scrap its position. The vote came after two roll calls in which members first refused, 46-44, and then agreed, 47-43, to kill a motion to insist on allowing federal Medicaid payments for abortions in promptly reported rape and incest cases. Abortion was the only area of disagreement between the two chambers in the huge spending bill for the departments of <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> and Education. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rejected the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> view last Friday, voting 216-166 to continue the current policy of federal funds only when an abortion is needed to save a woman's life. Sen. <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the subcommittee that handled the spending bill, pleaded with his colleagues to accept defeat and help enact the overall measure `` We're talking about a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> that we're 50 votes short in. We're talking about a president that's going to veto the bill. We're talking about a clock that's ticking,'' <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON> said. `` You can stand on principle forever and you'll have nothing, if you do n't know when you have to close that gap.''' The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 73-19 in July to expand Medicaid to pay for abortions in rape or incest cases that are promptly reported. States would have had the option of retaining the current, more limited policy. The abortion provision was part of the $ 140 billion Labor-HHS-Education measure for fiscal 1989, which begins Oct. 1. The bill contains money for medical research, job training, college loans and programs for disadvantaged children, among many other items. In a Sept. 7 letter to congressional leaders, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> reiterated his intention to veto the entire package if it came to him with the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s abortion provision. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> language would permit the use of federal funds for the salughter of unborn children, depriving the innocent of the most basic of civil rights _ the right to life,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> wrote. `` I urge the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to vote to protect the lives of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s unborn children.'' The rhetoric on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor Tuesday was equally intense. Sen. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikulski </PERSON>, D-Md., a social worker, said she vividly recalls the coat-hanger abortions suffered by poor women without access to the high-priced society doctors willing to perform underground abortions `` Abortion is a legal medical procedure that is now available to women who are well-off. Denying it to poor women is discrimination, pure and simple,'' she said. <PERSON> Mikulski </PERSON> also said that making a woman bear the child of her attacker is `` grotesque and inhumane.'' But Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, argued that a child conceived by rape is not `` any less of a human being than one who is not ... One atrocity ... does n't justify another. Rape does n't justify murder.'' Sen. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON>, R-Conn., who launched the crusade for wider federal abortion coverage, excoriated the administration for pressing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to the wall on the issue `` They're going to use their last gasp and their last piece of political capital'' to deny abortions to rape and incest victims, <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON> charged. `` What a legacy for an outgoing president.'' <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON>, who is up for re-election this year, acknowledged in advance that he was beaten on the floor vote. But he added, `` I think it's important that the record be established ... so people understand how they can respond on Election Day.'' The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Right-to-Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> termed the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> votes `` a sharp setback for the pro-abortion movement groups'' and said the administration's support had been `` extremely helpful.'' Fourteen states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> pay for Medicaid abortions but only receive federal reimbursement in life-threatening cases. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote in July was the first time since 1981 that either chamber of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had approved more liberal eligibility.
