<HEAD>Cool Weather Continues In Yellowstone</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Sierra Fires Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first Marines sent to help battle forest fires that have charred nearly 1 million acres of <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> arrived Tuesday as the wet weather that has helped quiet flames began to lift. The Marines will help bolster sagging firefighter numbers in the park and provide relief for fire crews that have been on fire lines for some time, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Valen </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` We knew we were losing our crews,'' he said. `` Some of them have been out there way past the usual 21-day assignement. Some need to get back to college. So we're rotating a lot of crews out.'' About 550 Marines flew into <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, from <LOCATION> Camp </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pendleton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, to help the estimated 7,200 firefighters still in the park battling fires that have plagued northwestern <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> since early July. However, <ORGANIZATION> Marines </ORGANIZATION> will have received only two days of training before they are placed on fire lines and will have to be accompanied by seasoned firefighters, <PERSON> Valen </PERSON> said, putting additional pressure on fire personnel. In all, 1,200 Marines are being sent, with 1,400 Army soldiers due from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lewis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, to double the number of military personnel assigned to the fires. By Tuesday, the fires had blackened 939,270 acres of the 2.2 million-acre park. Fires in the national forests and parks surrounding <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> bring the total burned acreage to 1.4 million acres. Fires also burned Tuesday in northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, where 8,000 people were evacuated from communities in an area northeast of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, which had its last big fire almost under control at 8500 acres. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state's biggest fire, in <ORGANIZATION> Colville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>, was declared contained at 20,126 acres. Controversy has surrounded the Yellowstone fires because of the <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s `` let burn'' policy, of not fighting most fires that start naturally. In past years such fires have remained small, but critics blame the policy for letting fires get out of control in this unusually dry summer. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said Tuesday he had not been aware of the policy, but said <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> told him `` we were withdrawing this policy.'' Colorado Gov. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> said Democratic presidential candidate <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would join him, <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwinden </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> on Thursday to survey fire damage in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> and discuss policy. <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was changing his campaign schedule for the meeting. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' campaign headquarters in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> had no immediate comment about any <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> appearance, said a media assistant, <PERSON> Tripp </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>. Rain that had fallen on parts of <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> since Saturday tapered off Tuesday, but had continued longer than expected. The forecast called for partial clearing by Wednesday and for temperatures to rise to the low 70s by Thursday. But the weather remained cool enough Tuesday that officials began distributing cold-weather gear donated by residents of communities around <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> to firefighters. Few firefighters had been prepared for the cold, wet weather that limited fire activity and the <ORGANIZATION> Salvation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and other organizations started collecting coats and other clothing to send to fire camps. Firefighters continued to take advantage of the cool weather to strengthen fire lines in anticipation of the warmer, drier weather. `` The fires are still a threat, we are not out of it yet,'' said fire information officer <PERSON> Sonya </PERSON> <PERSON> Capek </PERSON>. `` We know there is some more fire time left in the season, but hopefully it wo n't be as intense.'' Along the north side of the park in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, school resumed Tuesday in <PERSON> Gardiner </PERSON>, the park's northern entrance, after being closed Monday, but an evacuation plan was ready in case fires advanced, said <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> McBride </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Gallatin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>. Near <LOCATION> Cooke </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and Silver Gate just outside the park's northeast tip, rehabilitation work has already begun along fire lines flanking the 81,400-acre Storm Creek fire, which threatened the towns for several days last week Information officer <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Coffman </PERSON> said crews were smoothing dirt over bulldozed lines, repairing creek drainages and planting some fire lines.
