<HEAD>Gorbachev Blames Local Officials for Siberian City's Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> got an earful of complaints about housing and food problems in <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> for the second day in a row Tuesday, and then tore into local officials for mismanagement. `` I felt that it's already impossible to talk to the people,'' the Soviet leader said in a meeting with local officials in the city of <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION>. `` Wherever I was, on the street in a factory, or here, the people are simply at your throat. And I think they're right.'' His comments were included in an hourlong report about his visit on the Soviet television evening news program `` Vremya.'' The visit has received heavy TV coverage, emphasizing the importance of his message. The official Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON>, also a member of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Politburo </ORGANIZATION>, discussed housing and other problems of everyday life on Tuesday with workers in the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Vladivostok </LOCATION>. The public appearances by both men seemed to be part of a <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> effort to show concern about poor living conditions. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has made the issue of improving the daily lives of average Soviets a key element of his policy of perestroika, or restructuring of Soviet society. He has said he is not satisfied with the efforts made so far. The Politburo has called for building enough new housing to give every family its own apartment by the year 2000. Local officials tried to explain their approaches to solving the region's problems, but were clearly embarrassed by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s criticism One <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> official told <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> that <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> residents receive the government's recommended yearly allotment of 154 pounds of meat, but the Soviet leader retorted that people laugh at such standards. He said Chinese and Japanese eat much less meat, `` but everyone who goes there says everything is on the shelf to buy. That's the story. People are laughing at these scientifically based norms.'' Soviet citizens shown on televised reports of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s frequent visits around the country usually praise his policies, or ask uncritical questions But <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> ran into loud complaints about life in <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> upon flying to the Siberian city, about 2,000 miles east of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, following a six-week vacation. He said the slow rate of development in the huge <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> region was a constant topic of concern in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. The region encompasses one-tenth of the entire <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, produces half of its coal and 20 percent of its forest products. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said the government has invested billions of rubles in the area and is getting little in return. He told workers at the Khimvolokno synthetic fiber factory in <LOCATION> Krasnoyarsk </LOCATION> that the Politburo was giving special attention to a shortage of kindergartens. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> quoted one worker as shooting back: `` We have kindergartens! We do n't have housing, and the medical facilities are bad.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> heard similar complaints Monday when he stopped in <LOCATION> Yemelyanovo </LOCATION> village on his way to <LOCATION> Kransoyarsk </LOCATION> from the airport after arriving from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. `` We have no hot water! You do what you can to wash!,'' one man shouted at the 57-year-old Communist Party chief. `` I'll tell you right off, comrades, that we can not count on successful perestroika if the people ... -LRB- have -RRB- got so many problems piling up to form a single big problem, that of inadequate social amenities,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. He spoke frequently about environmental problems, criticizing `` gigantomania'' _ the propensity to build huge factories and power stations regardless of their impact on the environment. Too often projects `` carried out under the flag of Communism threaten nature, and the interests of the people are considered last,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said that on <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON>'s visit to <LOCATION> Vladivostok </LOCATION>, workers at the <PERSON> Dalvostok </PERSON> ship repair yard complained about work and living conditions, medical care, shortages of consumer goods and cultural amenities.
