<HEAD>Federal Commission Says Teacher Test Biased</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has ruled that a literacy test all <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> teachers were required to pass to keep their jobs discriminated against teachers who were black or over 40. State officials said they do not agree with the ruling and plan to negotiate with the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> in an attempt to modify or reverse the decision. A summary of the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> ruling was released by the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` We said all along that the test was discriminatory toward blacks and older teachers,'' said <PERSON> Ollie </PERSON> <PERSON> Besteiro </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` This means that school districts will have to go back and review their records to see which former teachers might be eligible for reinstatement, back pay or pension adjustments,'' <PERSON> Besteiro </PERSON> said. In the spring of 1986, teachers and school administrators had two chances to pass the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Examination of Current Administrators and Teachers, or TECAT. Out of the estimated 200,000 teachers and administrators in the state, 1,875 failed the test and were not qualified to work in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> schools that fall. `` Failure rates for blacks and older persons indicated that the TECAT adversely impacts on blacks and persons within the protected age group under -LRB- federal law -RRB- who were either applicants or employees for teaching positions in the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> public school system in 1986,'' the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> said. State figures showed a passing rate for whites of 99.9 percent, compared to 98.9 percent for Hispanics and 95.4 percent for blacks. State education Commissioner <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON> challenged the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> decision, said the same statewide results showed that 99.29 percent of educators under age 40 passed the test, while 99.64 percent of teachers over 40 passed. `` Older educators did better on the test than younger ones. The results clearly refute the contention that the test discriminated against individuals on the basis of age,'' he said Tuesday. `` The test was a fair and accurate measure of the examinees' basic reading and writing skills that was in no way influenced by race or age,'' <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON> said He said another federal agency, the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, had looked at the test and `` found no evidence whatsoever of racial discrimination.'' The <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> ruling was made in response to complaints filed by several of the failed teachers against their school districts, the state and the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, which approved the content and passing score of the exam. The teachers association represented the teachers before the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, legal counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, argued the <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> erred in its findings about the literacy test. `` We do n't think their findings are factually or legally valid,'' he said. `` I think they got their facts wrong and failed to consider some legal precedents that affect the case.'' State attorneys are negotiating with <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> officials before taking any action, said <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> officials had asked for additional information, including the civil rights report. `` We are confident they will revise their decision when they review the complete information,'' he said.
