<FIRST>r w AM-UndergroundTanks     09-13 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Underground Tanks,000</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Issues Regulations On Underground Tanks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday issued a 370-page set of regulations that requires almost all owners of underground tanks, including the corner gasoline station, to test and protect their tanks, fix leaks and clean up spills. One set of requirements applies to all tanks installed after December of this year. Another set gradually applies to the nearly 2 million existing tanks _ 97 percent of them holding gasoline or other petroleum products _ and makes them generally meet the new tank standards in December 1998. The first requirement to bite is that existing tanks more than 25 years old must have leak detection systems _ which may be inventory checks and annual tightness tests _ installed in the coming year, with the requirement applying to the youngest tanks in 1993. Corrosion protection systems and spill and overfilling prevention devices would be required only in 1998. About 80 percent of the tanks in use are steel tanks without protection against rust. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> says its surveys show that anywhere from 10 percent to 30 percent of the 750,000 tank locations have, or have had, significant leaks. Only about 5 percent of existing tanks have leak detection systems. The regulations, four years in the drafting, require double-walled tanks or similar double-barrier protection only for some 60,000 chemical tanks, and one environmental group immediately criticized the agency for the omission. Failure to require double barriers for petroleum product tanks means `` EPA is leaving the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> supply of drinking water vulnerable to petroleum contamination,'' said staff scientists <PERSON> Lois </PERSON> <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON> of the Environmental Defense Fund. `` The regulations are designed to minimize their impact on the regulated community, not to protect the environment and the public from the hzards of petroleum contamination,'' she said. But <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Winston </PERSON> <PERSON> Porter </PERSON>, assistant <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator with jurisdiction over the tank program, said that `` secondary containment is quite expensive'' and would add unspecified billions to the cost of the final regulations. One of his staff, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, said a double-barrier requirement would add $ 80,000 to the cost of a new three-tank service station, and existing stations would have to rip out all their tanks if the requirement were imposed on existing installations. Such a station might have to spend $ 3,000 to $ 8,000 on a leak detection system and $ 10,000 to $ 48,000 on an electrical rust-prevention system, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> estimated. As it stands, the agency estimated that tank owners will have to spend the equivalent of $ 54 billion in today's dollars, but the owners and society will reap $ 73 billion worth of benefits in reduced damage, inventory losses and cleanup costs. It did not present an estimate of the extra costs and benefits associated with double barriers, nor did it estimate health benefits from less contamination of groundwater. `` Whether you're mom and pop or <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, it does n't make a lot of sense to keep a leaking gasoline tank in the ground. The liability is enormous,'' <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> said. About a dozen states already have tank regulations of their own in place, and part of Tuesday's regulatory package was the announcement of procedures by which states can win approval of those programs from <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>. A state does not have to have a program at all, which would leave <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to enforce the new regulations. <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> said the agency at this point had made no provision for operating tank programs, and `` we hope very few'' states will opt out. Still to come in about six weeks are regulations prescribing financial responsibilities of tank owners. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administers a $ 500 million fund to help pay for cleanups. The regulations exempt septic tanks, tanks of 1,100 gallons or less storing fuel for farm or non-commercial use, home heating oil tanks and tanks on basement floors, which are considered above-ground tanks. The regulations take effect 90 days from publication, expected soon in the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Register </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
