<HEAD>Reagan Says Democrats Would `License' Grandmothers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs of Dodd reax after 8th graf, ``And that;''
notes in 11th graf that subcommittee headed by Dodd; corrects
``qualification'' to ``qualifications'' in last graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said Tuesday that Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s child care plan would help provide children with `` tender, loving family care'' while the Democratic plan favored by <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would lead to `` licensing grandmothers.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> candidate for president, has proposed a plan to give tax credits of up to $ 1,000 to assist families with child care. The money could be used either to pay for outside child care or to enable a mother to stay home and take care of her children instead of working. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the Democratic presidential candidate, has endorsed a bill by Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., providing for the federal government to reimburse providers of child care The providers would have to meet federal standards in order to receive the funds. <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> said recently that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposed tax credit was `` as likely to be used for household expenses'' as for care of children and would fall far short of the $ 3,000 average annual cost per family for child care. He also said it would fail to repay the wages lost by a mother who stays home. But <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, speaking at a Rose Garden ceremony at which he signed a proclamation setting the current week aside as <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hispanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Week </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan `` will allow parents to choose among a variety of options if they need child care assistance.'' `` Experts tell us what common sense always has _ the best people to take care of children are family members,'' the president said. `` And that's the kind of care that <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan will help provide _ tender, loving, family care. `` Now, compare this plan with the one offered by the liberals. They've written a bill that gives assistance not to the parent, but to the person who provides the care. And why? Because they want to make sure that they have control over the kind of care your child receives. `` And that means if you want to leave your child with his grandmother during the day, she will have to be licensed under federal standards if she's to be given assistance for helping to raise her grandhild. Licensing grandmothers. Can you believe it? Well, I think it's terrible, and I do n't think the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people are going to stand for it.'' <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> commented, `` No one is worried about the kinds who are left in their grandmother's care; in a perfect world, every infant and every young child would have a parent or grandparent who could stay at home and look after him. `` What we are worried about and what the Act for <ORGANIZATION> Better </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> will address is the millions of children whose parents do n't have that option, who work for a living and have to leave their kids in the hands of strangers _ in day care centers and family day care homes. That's where we need at least some minimum health, safety and competency standards.'' <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> Isaacson </PERSON>, press secretary for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on children and the family, headed by <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, said it was true that a grandmother would have to meet federal standards in order to receive funds under the bill. `` How else can you design a program that receives federal funds?'' he asked. `` You just ca n't give federal funds out without some assurance that they are not going to be used for child neglect and abuse. We are not worried about grandmothers; we are worried about 16 - and 17-year-olds and people who have no training and no qualifications.
