<FIRST>r w AM-Corn-Soviets     09-13 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Corn-Soviets,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets to Buy 350,000 More Metric Tons of Corn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has bought an additional 350,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn for delivery during the coming year, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. The sale brought total corn sold to the Soviets in the last two weeks for the 1988-89 delivery year that started Sept. 1 to more than 2.95 million tons. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 350,000 tons of corn would be about 13.8 million bushels. Corn prices have been averaging about $ 2.73 per bushel at the farm level, according to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> estimates, meaning that the latest sale could have a farm value of around $ 38 million. As with the other recent sales, no indication was given whether the new sales of corn to the Soviets would count under the current long-term grain supply agreement between the two countries or be carried forward separately in case a new pact is forthcoming. The current five-year pact is set to expire Sept. 30 and negotiators are trying to work out a new one, or at least an extension of the current agreement, to take effect on Oct. 1. According to the agreement, the annual purchases are supposed to include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn. The Soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as wheat, corn or soybeans, with every ton of beans counting as two tons of grain _ up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain equivalent. Prior to sales announced since Sept. 1, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had purchased 9.05 million tons of wheat and 5.17 million tons of corn for delivery in the fifth year of the agreement, plus 830,000 tons of soybeans and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal.
</TEXT>
