<FIRST>u w AM-DebonedMeat     09-13 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deboned Meat,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Aide Opposed Change in Product Labels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> proposal to allow up to 10 percent salvaged meat and tiny bone chips in hot dogs without telling consumers about it on product labels was made over the objections of a White House regulatory aide, documents disclosed Tuesday. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Plager </PERSON>, administrator of information and regulatory affairs in the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> in a letter Aug. 19 that the proposed rule change `` does not appear to be consistent with several of the administration's basic regulatory principles.'' `` Nor does it appear that the potential benefits to society of this regulation outweigh the potential cost to society,'' <PERSON> Plager </PERSON> added. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s general counsel, replied that department officials `` do not agree with the conclusions'' set forth by <PERSON> Plager </PERSON>. `` There are compelling reasons for proposing this rule, including the fact that it may produce benefits to society that outweigh societal costs,'' <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> told <PERSON> Plager </PERSON> in a Sept. 6 letter. Copies of the letters by <PERSON> Plager </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON> were provided to The Associated Press. Advocates of the rule change contend that consumers wo n't buy products containing the salvaged material if labels inform them about it. The proposal, which began a 60-day rulemaking procedure Sept. 9, was announced Monday by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. It involves the use of `` mechanically separated'' meat, or <ORGANIZATION> MSM </ORGANIZATION>, although current regulations describe it as MS -LRB- S -RRB- to acknowledge the species of animal involved. Thus, salvaged meat from a hog would be mechanically separated pork, or MSP. According to the plan, which will be open for public comment until Nov. 8, processors would be able to use MS -LRB- S -RRB- to comprise up to 10 percent of the meat in franks, bologna, luncheon meats, sausage and similar products without stating so on product labels. However, the label would have to indicate the percentage of the Recommended Daily Allowance of calcium that the product contained. Calcium is a primary ingredient of bone tissue. Regulations limit the salvaged product to no more than 0.75 percent calcium. But bones are about one-fourth calcium, so that would translate into a maximum of about 3 percent bone. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Meat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a private association that represents meat packers and processors, said in a statement that the use of calcium on labels would be `` a more meaningful and useful term'' to consumers than MS -LRB- S -RRB-, particularly to those who have a calcium deficiency and to a few who are allergic to calcium and should be warned away from such products. `` There is no wholesomeness or safety issue involved'' in the MS -LRB- S -RRB- proposal, the institute said in the brief statement, citing the department's own description of the product as `` safe and wholesome as the species from which it is derived.'' But <PERSON> Plager </PERSON> said the assertion that consumers would avoid products labeled as containing MS -LRB- S -RRB- had not been documented in the proposed rule change. `` Furthermore, if one accepts the assertion that some consumers would be reluctant to purchase a product that they know to contain MS -LRB- S -RRB-, why should this information be omitted from the label?'' he said. `` Would its omission, in other words, be inconsistent with the <ORGANIZATION> FSIS </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- obligation to prevent labels that are ` false or misleading' and, hence, contrary to <ORGANIZATION> FSIS </ORGANIZATION>' statutory mission to protect the public from misbranded items? <PERSON> Plager </PERSON> said that in seeking ways to carry out less burdensome food safety regulations, `` We must also provide consumers with more, rather than less, information about food products so that they may reach informed market decisions.'' Under current regulations, MS -LRB- S -RRB- can comprise up to 20 percent of the meat portion of these products, but the labels must state that the products contain MS -LRB- S -RRB-. The department said that under the proposed rule change _ which was sought by a group of meat processors and supported by the trade _ MS -LRB- S -RRB- `` would not have to be listed in the ingredients statement on the label as long as it does not exceed 10 percent'' of the meat portion of the finished product. When animals are slaughtered, most of the red meat is cut or scraped from bones by hand. But a lot of edible tissue clings to the bones and gristle, particularly in neck bones, ribs, joints and other hard-to-scrape places. The bones and the attached meat remnants are put through a grinder and forced through fine sieves. Although most of the bones are strained out, the resulting mixture still contains bits of bone about the size of ground pepper. According to the meat processors who asked <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> for the rule change, no company at present is commercially producing MS -LRB- S -RRB- for consumer products because of `` unwarranted negative connotations'' associated with the term MS -LRB- S -RRB-. Under various names, MS -LRB- S -RRB- has been authorized for use in the meat products since 1978 and has undergone numerous legal challenges from consumer groups opposed to the salvaged product itself or labeling requirements.
