<HEAD>Pentagon Re-Creates Slice Of Soviet Military Machine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Pentagon has re-created a tiny slice of the Soviet military machine to serve as a mobile laboratory for testing American weapons and equipment. The unusual amalgamation of enemy gear is now undergoing its first operational test at <ORGANIZATION> Kirtland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, the Pentagon announced Tuesday. Known formally as the Mobile Integrated Threat Test, the setup replicates `` a key slice of a Soviet Army headquarters and division organization'' and uses real enemy equipment obtained through a variety of means, officials said. Most of the equipment is electronic _ primarily radar and radio gear. But MiG jet fighters also will be used in simulating the `` threat force,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> added in a statement. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military has long conducted tests and experiments with pieces of military equipment made in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> and Third World countries and then captured, stolen or covertly purchased. What makes the new effort different is an attempt to combine the radar, radios and targeting equipment into the type of `` integrated'' system that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces would face on a battlefield. Also setting the work apart is the creation of a small organization known as the Defense Test and Evaluation Support Agency that is responsible for operating the gear and playing the enemy. `` We're not re-inventing the wheel; bits and portions of this have been done in the past,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, the director of the Mobile Integrated Threat Test. `` What we're going to offer is the ability to deliver, set up and operate this -LRB- enemy -RRB- gear for testing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> systems. We're trying ... to come close to the real thing The gear we have is not state-of-the-art, but it's still in use within the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact.'' The tests now under way at <LOCATION> Kirtland </LOCATION> are designed to demonstrate that a relatively large network of Soviet equipment can be operated just like the Russians would handle it. Once that goal is accomplished, the support agency will respond to requests from the military services for assistance in checking out the effectiveness of various types of American equipment. The <LOCATION> Kirtland </LOCATION> tests, which will run to early October, will include some flights by Soviet aircraft `` simulating close-air support missions'' as well as flights by <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> A-7 attack jets. The A-7s will be used `` to test the capabilities of the Soviet sensors,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> statement said. `` But this is not a traveling road show,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. `` There wo n't be any dogfights or anything like that. We do n't want to oversell what we're doing.''
