<HEAD>Air Force Says Most Spectators To Be Moved Away From Shuttle
Launch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Spectators and journalists in the traditional shuttle launch viewing area have one chance in a thousand of being killed from an out-of-control rocket booster, the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. For that reason, said Col. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gooch </PERSON>, visitors and more than half the journalists expected for the Discovery liftoff later this month will be placed at a site 6 -LCB- miles away from the launch pad, instead of the usual 3 -LCB- miles. The chance of being killed by an exploding booster at the more remote site is hundred times less _ or, one in 100,000 _ said <PERSON> Gooch </PERSON>, the commander of the Eastern Space and Missile Center at <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>. The Air force is responsible for safety in the entire area which is dotted with launch pads. More than 3,600 members of the news media already have applied for credentials and the total is expected to rise to more than 4,000, said <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> public affairs chief <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON>. He said all news media who need to be at the close-in press site at the moment of launch will be accommodated, the maximum number being about 1,800. The journalists who will be moved will be those who do n't have immediate deadlines, such as weekly newsmagazines, <PERSON> Sheehan </PERSON> said. He issued guidelines for credentials: as many as 40 for each of the major television networks, 10 for each wire service, two each for daily newspapers, six each for small television networks, four each for radio networks, three each for individual television stations and two each for individual radio stations. The rest of the credentialed journalists will be put at the remote site, where there are no telephones and only minimal services. The general public, which has turned out a million strong for some past launches on the roads near the Kennedy Space Center, will not be affected because admittance to the center is restricted. The changes were ordered, <PERSON> Gooch </PERSON> said, because the booster rockets did not tumble end over end when the Challenger exploded, but instead continued to fly `` in a missile mode.'' In the case of the Challenger, they went out over the sea. But if they had returned to land, they would have had to be destroyed by command of the range safety officer, scattering shrapnel over the area, <PERSON> Gooch </PERSON> said. `` We can never guarantee absolute safety but we can minimize the risk by minimizing the number of folks,'' said <PERSON> Gooch </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Greene </PERSON>, a veteran shuttle flight director and chairman of a <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> risk analysis team said, `` The risk hazard has n't increased since -LRB- the Challenger accident -RRB- ... we understand the risk better.'' Asked if the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> was imposing censorship under the guise of public safety, <PERSON> Gooch </PERSON> replied: `` I believe we are addressing the safety issue.''
