<FIRST>r w AM-LabLicensing     09-13 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lab Licensing,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Passes Legislation to Require Federal Licenses for Medical
Labs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House on Tuesday approved legislation that would for the first time require all medical laboratories _ including nearly 100,000 such labs in doctors' offices nationwide _ to be federally licensed. Such laboratories perform four billion to six billion tests a year for diagnosis and monitoring of disease, and some have been criticized because of rushed procedures that can lead to mistakes. Under the bill, passed on a voice vote, all medical labs would have to meet quality control, personnel and equipment standards and would be subject to penalties for violations. All laboratories would be licensed for two years at a time, would have to pass proficiency tests and would have to meet specific, stringent standards for evaluations of Pap smears which are used to detect cervical cancer. There have been charges that private labs that process thousands of Pap smears daily have been careless in efforts to maximize profits and on occasion failed to spot cases of cancer. Backers of the legislation said there are some 4,500 independent labs in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, 6,600 hospital laboratories and 98,000 labs in doctors' offices. The labs would be required to pay issuance and renewal fees for their federal certificates. The measure now goes to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> for further action. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has not expressed a position on the bill. Current law subjects hospital and independent laboratories to regulation, but does not affect labs in physicians' offices. The bill would require doctors' - office labs to be certified in order to receive reimbursement for Medicaid and Medicare cases beginning Certain relatively simple tests done in doctors' offices, such as pregnancy tests, diabetes tests and certain urine tests, would be exempted from the legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
