<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Pope, <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> clash,'' said a headline Tuesday in one South African newspaper. `` <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> in agreement,'' said a headline in another. The conflicting messages reflected the intense battle being waged by South African political factions to capitalize on Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>'s visit to five neighboring countries. The pope is bypassing <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, but his comments on issues such as apartheid, sanctions and political violence are being analyzed and interpreted here with great intensity and diversity. Pro-government media seized upon some of the pope's comments en route to <LOCATION> Harare </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, on Saturday and suggested that he had repudiated Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>. This interpretation was based on the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>'s unqualified denunciation of political violence, and his reservations about sanctions and election boycotts. <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> advocates sanctions and is urging a boycott of the upcoming segregated elections. He has repeatedly condemned violence but says he understands how some South African blacks feel they have no other alternative in seeking to end white-minority domination. One pro-government paper, <ORGANIZATION> Beeld </ORGANIZATION>, ran a cartoon Tuesday showing <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> with a chain of bullets around his neck. `` Is this what your rosary looks like?'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> asks <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>, as they stand near a newspaper poster that reads: `` Pope Strongly Against Sanctions and Violence.'' `` It is a pity that Archbishop <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> was not in <LOCATION> Harare </LOCATION> to hear the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>, since he would have learned what a man of such eminence has to say in leading the faithful on the paths of reconciliation and peace,'' said The Citizen, a pro-government daily, in an editorial Monday. `` But then, the pope is a great religious leader, whereas Archbishop <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON> has decided to involve himself in politics.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> also was praised by the state-run South African <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. In a commentary Tuesday, it contrasted his `` forthright declarations'' with the `` vagueness, prevarication and endless qualifications'' from South African clergymen. <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>'s spokesman, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, said there are no fundamental differences between the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> and the archbishop, who met earlier this year at the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. Both oppose violence and agree that strategies such as sanctions and election boycotts should not be used indiscriminately, if other effective tactics were available, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said. The papal visit also has prompted ideological maneuvering in Marxist-ruled <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> will travel there Friday on the last leg of his trip. The government-backed newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Noticias </ORGANIZATION>, in a front-page editorial Monday, said the visit to <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> proves that the pope sides with `` the peoples of southern <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'' in a struggle against `` the forces of colonialism, apartheid and destabilization.'' The editorial denounced the `` hesitations, ambiguities or collaborationist silence'' of local <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> leaders who have urged the government to change its policy and negotiate with the <ORGANIZATION> Mozambique </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION> guerrilla movement.
