saying it unlikely, comments from Secretary of State Shultz,
details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> UNITED </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> NATIONS </ORGANIZATION> _ Ten nations have called on the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to investigate claims that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> used poison gas in an attempt to crush the Kurdish rebellion in its country, an official said Tuesday. Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> conveyed the request to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s charge d'affaires, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahmoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Sumaida </PERSON>, said <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Nadia </PERSON> <PERSON> Younes </PERSON>. <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Okun </PERSON>, the second-ranking diplomat at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Mission to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, made the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> request Monday to <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>. <PERSON> Okun </PERSON> acted on behalf of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, said a spokeswoman for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mission, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The other nations who requested the investigation were <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>, she said. In <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, an <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> official said Tuesday his country probably would not admit the proposed <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> team to conduct the investigation. `` This is considered a question of sovereignty and therefore I do not think we are going to accept that,'' said the official, who demanded anonymity. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has denied charges that it used poison gas in a bloody offensive against Kurdish guerrillas, a minority people living in northern <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and eastern <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> who are fighting for a separate homeland in northern <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> acknowledged on July 1 that it used chemical weapons during its nearly 8-year-old war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> but claimed the Iranians had used them first. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said Tuesday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has `` compelling'' evidence that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has used chemical weapons against its Kurdish citizens. But he said the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> should conduct its own probe before being asked to condemn <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> for alleged genocide. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> reached the conclusion <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> was using chemical weapons against the Kurds based on an examination of Kurdish refugees in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and on `` other evidence which to me seems to be compelling.'' About 60,000 Kurds recently fled <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, citing poison gas attacks. `` I feel our evidence is quite convincing ...'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. `` But we're not in a position to make that public.'' The evidence led the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Friday to vote for tough economic sanctions against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The measure still must be approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and signed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. In <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, about 150 Kurds demonstrated outside the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> office Tuesday, calling for the world body to investigate the alleged gas attacks and shouting `` <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON>, assassin,'' a reference to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> In <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> on Tuesday, <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` is determined the use of chemical warfare will not become an accepted part of regional conflicts.'' <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> spoke to reporters during a tour of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> to discuss issues to be considered at the 43rd session of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, which convenes Sept. 20 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said it wants an investigation partly because of <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> evidence of chemical attacks. The <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said it also based its decision on other evidence, including reports from Western journalists in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> who have seen Kurdish refugees they say are suffering from poison gas injuries. However, <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> said Friday it found no evidence of the use of chemical weapons while examining sick and injured refugees. In <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that charges of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s use of chemical weapons were `` fallacious.'' In <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> criticized the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> sanctions, and a <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official said the accusations against <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> were groundless. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> concluded in August following an investigation that `` chemical weapons continue to be used on an intensive scale against Iranian forces.'' In March, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> claimed the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> air force dropped cyanide and mustard gas bombs on three Kurdish towns in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, killing 5,000 Kurds and injuring 5,000. The towns targeted by the attack had been captured by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The 1925 <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> Protocol bans the use of chemical or biological weapons, although their manufacture and stockpiling is allowed to deter attack.
