<HEAD>Stalled Iran-Iraq Talks To Shift To New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The U.N.-sponsored peace talks between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, stalled since they started almost three weeks ago, went into recess Tuesday and will move temporarily to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> hopes to unblock the negotiations at <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters there. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mediator <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Eliasson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> said both sides accepted an invitation by <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> to continue direct talks `` soon'' at <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. He said they agreed to return to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> for subsequent meetings. <PERSON> Eliasson </PERSON> has been presiding over the talks since last week as the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief's personal representative. He said <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> invited foreign ministers <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Velayati </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Tariq </PERSON> <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> to meet in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Sept. 22. But the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> delegation said in a statement issued Tuesday night that <PERSON> Aziz </PERSON> could not be in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> before the first week of October. The statement indicated that acceptance of `` one meeting'' in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> was conditional on agreeing on a binding date for reconvening the talks in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Eliasson </PERSON> told a news conference earlier Tuesday that both <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> `` seem committed to keep the peace process going'' and both confirmed that they will continue to observe the cease-fire. The truce went into effect Aug. 20 after nearly eight years of fighting and about 1 million dead or wounded. The talks in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> began on Aug. 25. <PERSON> Eliasson </PERSON> conceded that `` on issues of substance there has been little if any progress'' but said the most important thing at this stage was that `` the peace process is kept alive.'' The talks bogged down over differing priorities. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> wants them to stick to implementation of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> cease-fire resolution 598, starting with withdrawal of `` all forces to the internationally recognized boundaries without delay.'' <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> wants the negotiations to focus first on clearing the <LOCATION> Shatt-el-Arab </LOCATION> waterway, its main link to the sea, and on freedom of negotiation in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>.
