<SECOND>AM-Obit-Hargreaves,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roger Hargreaves, Creator of `Mister Men' Children's Stories, 53</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Hargreaves </PERSON>, who turned his deskpad doodlings into the popular `` Mister Men'' and `` Little Miss'' storybooks for children, died of a heart attack at his home near <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, death notices said Tuesday. He was 53. The Times of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Hargreaves </PERSON> died Monday. <PERSON> Hargreaves </PERSON>, a laundryman's son, was born in the northern English county of <LOCATION> Yorkshire </LOCATION> and went into advertising after service in the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. His career prospered but he said boredom turned him to writing children's stories. Combining his doodles with bed-time stories he made up for his own children, it took <PERSON> Hargreaves </PERSON> just two weeks to find a publisher and in 1972 his first six stories went on sale. They introduced young readers to Mister Bump, Mister Strong and <PERSON> Mister </PERSON> <PERSON> Sneezy </PERSON>. In 1981 he began a series featuring such characters as Little Miss Fussy and Little Miss Sunshine. His texts were simple and his drawings childlike _ bold colors, a few lines, some squares and dots. The books, published in soft cover, were inexpensive. Some 85 million are in circulation, translated into 22 languages. The stories have more than 750 characters and spinoffs include a television cartoon series and childrens' cups and plates, stationery and clothing. <PERSON> Hargreaves </PERSON> is survived by a wife, two daughters, two sons, and a granddaughter.
