09-13 0896</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan-Forest Fires, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0782,860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials to Reagan: No Word on When Western Forest Fires Will
Burn Out</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after pvs 19th graf bgng ``Answering
questions...'' to add Fitzwater comment on let-burn policy</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fires Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> got a grim report on the status of the nation's forest fires on Tuesday and was told there is no way to predict when the blazes will be tamed. `` We are fighting with everything at hand,'' <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. The spokesman met with reporters after <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was briefed on the forest fire situation by <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> and Deputy Defense Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> at the White House. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> described their session with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as an `` update'' and said there were no new efforts to be announced following the session. `` No one could give a prognosis of when the fires would be put out, but it is clear that we have dedicated all of the resources available and all of our energies, and the goal is the same for everyone _ and that is, put those fires out,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. The meeting came as thousands of firefighters continued to battle blazes in eight states, particularly <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state. It also followed harsh words on the government's `` let-burn'' approach to the fires from a usually strong <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration supporter, Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, who called the situation `` a catastrophe.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, asked if the president had been given a `` worst-case scenario'' of the devastation in the briefing, shot back, `` We are in the worst case.'' He did note later, however, that some of the officials had expressed `` some cautious optimism'' about prospects for calming the fires. <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> and <PERSON> Taft </PERSON> had traveled West to review the situation over the weekend. `` The president has been assured that we have been doing everything possible,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. He noted that some 30,000 firefighters were involved in battling 32 fires in eight Western states, with approximately 4 million acres burned. With the most recently dispatched military personnel on station by mid-week, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said, some 2,300 soldiers and 22 aircraft had been sent to Yellowstone National Park alone to battle the fires. `` The president has repeatedly expressed his concern for the people living in the fire areas, for the welfare of their families, for their businesses and occupations, and for the hardship that has undoubtedly consumed their lives,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. He called the situation `` a natural disaster of unprecendented proportions'' and said the people in the area and government officials `` have responded with great selflessness and determination to get the situation under control.'' `` We will continue to work tirelessly to put out these fires,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> pledged. Earlier in the day, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had said he'd not been aware of a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> policy permitting some forest lands to burn, and said that the policy has been scrapped. Asked what he thought of the so-called `` let-burn'' policy that has been carried out by the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in recent years, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told reporters, `` I have questioned it. I did not even know it existed, frankly.'' Answering questions as he headed back into the Oval Office after signing the fair housing bill, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said that when <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> last weekend, `` he made it plain that ... we were withdrawing from this policy.'' Asked how the administration planned to deal with any new outbreaks of fires, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the `` let burn'' policy had been dropped in July and that all new fires would be put out. The spokesman refused to entertain any discussion of the criticism of the administration's controversial policy. But he noted that since the nation has never faced such an outbreak of fires before, the time `` certainly calls for some review of the policy.'' `` It's not a clear case of what's right and what's wrong,'' he said. `` At this point, what's clear is that the fires are out of control. ... We have extraordinary drought conditions and there is no need to argue over policy differences until we come up with the next firefighting season next year. Right now, its all-out, fight-the-fires.'' The government's let-burn policy has been harshly criticized by <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> members from the Western states. <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, speaking to reporters after visiting the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` We all knew how dry it was and a lot of us were saying, ` Hey, Do n't let this burn and they could have contained it at that time.''' Some 8,000 firefighters have worked in past days to dampen fires in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, where the historic fires have charred 939,270 acres of the 2.2 million-acre park since June. Referring to the damage done to <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> went on: `` Now you have a million acres lost in one of the most important national park areas in the world. ... It's a catastrophe ...'' Without explanation the senator added, `` I suspect it comes from just too much extremism in the environmental area and a lot of our people in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> are very disappointed, very disenchanted about it.'' House Republican leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON>, emerging from a meeting of <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> congressional leaders with the president earlier, also said that he had not been aware of the policy. `` This let-burn policy obviously is going to come under review,'' <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> said.
