<HEAD>Priest A Hero To Poor, Villain To Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Haiti, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PIERRE-YVES GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Rev. <PERSON> Jean-Bertrand </PERSON> <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> is a hero to the poor and hated by the government, a target of both adulation and assassination for his outspoken criticism of <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>'s military regime The Roman Catholic priest was saying morning Mass last Sunday when 20 to 30 thugs armed with knives, machetes and guns burst into the St. <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> church in <LOCATION> Port-Au-Prince </LOCATION> and randomly slaughtered worshipers. Six people were confirmed dead and 77 wounded, witnesses and hospital officials said. Despite the carnage, witnesses said parishioners surrounded the priest and protected him with their bodies, sweeping him to safety and into hiding. <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> is perhaps the most popular figure among <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>'s slum-dwelling masses. During his sermons, in which he vigorously denounced army terror and atrocities, his small, cement-block church in the La Saline slum was regularly packed with exuberant, sometimes hysterical supporters. He has often led them into the streets for demonstrations during periods of unrest. `` Satan is eating us everywhere,'' <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> said of the army during a wave of anti-government demonstrations and harsh repression in June and July of 1987. `` They -LRB- the army -RRB- are the savages. Those who load their guns and shoot our children.'' Since the riots that summer, gunmen in speeding cars have frequently sprayed gunfire at the wall of his church's compound and the homes of other Salesian priests close to <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON>. On Aug. 23, 1987, <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> and four other priests were ambushed near <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marc </LOCATION> on the main north-south highway 60 miles north of the capital, <LOCATION> Port-au-Prince </LOCATION>. As they returned from a Mass in memory of a recent peasant massacre, about 40 men armed with machine guns, stones and clubs attacked their car, injuring two of the priests. Soldiers at a checkpoint 70 yards away did not intervene. <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> escaped and went into hiding for several weeks following the incident. During a Sunday Mass on Sept. 4, a man entered <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON>'s church with a gun stuck in his belt. The man fled after parishioners wrestled him to the ground and seized the pistol. <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON>'s name and those of other opposition leaders are on a `` death list'' of people marked for assassination which has circulated in <LOCATION> Port-au-Prince </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON>, who preaches that Marxism and Christianity are compatible, has not actually called for an armed uprising, but repeatedly advocated the overthrow of the Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON>'s military government by `` active non-violent struggle. The conservative hierarchy of the church has rejected <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON>'s `` notion of class struggle. In April the church leadership apparently attempted to <PERSON> rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> of his power base _ the capital's slums _ by transferring him to a remote rural parish north of <LOCATION> Port-au-Prince </LOCATION>. For several days a dozen of his youthful followers occupied the Notre Dame Cathedral in the capital and went on a hunger strike which forced the bishops to rescind their order. <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON>, in his mid-30s, was ordained by his uncle, <PERSON> Bishop </PERSON> <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Romelus </PERSON> of the western town of <PERSON> Jeremie </PERSON>, who is the only openly anti-military member of <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>'s 10-member Bishops Conference. Although the bishops have never called for the overthrow of <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON>'s government, they issued a statement last month that echoed one made by Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> during a tour of <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> in 1983 which said `` things must change'' in the impoverished nation. The statement protested the expulsion of a priest, the assassination of human rights leader <PERSON> Lafontant </PERSON> <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> in July and accused the military government of authoritarian rule and disregard for human life. Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON>'s visit helped crystalize public repudiation of the dictatorship of <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON>, who fled to exile in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> on Feb. 7, 1986.
