<HEAD>Bush Pulling Ahead in Two New Polls</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two national polls Tuesday found <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> pulling past <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in the presidential race, and they indicated that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has scored points by pressing the <ORGANIZATION> Pledge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allegiance </ORGANIZATION> as an issue. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> led by eight points in both national surveys, 47-39 percent in a <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> poll and 49-41 percent in a Gallup poll. The Gallup poll found <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> suffering his highest negative rating of the race. Two polls released Monday showed a closer race, but two surveys last week found <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> leading by six and eight points respectively. Moreover, the new polls found support for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on underlying issues he has been pressing. On defense, 28 percent of the probable voters in the <ORGANIZATION> CBS-Times </ORGANIZATION> poll said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would make the nation stronger and only 4 percent said he would make it weaker. By contrast, 39 percent said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would make <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> defenses weaker, and just 13 percent said he would make the nation stronger. The rest in both cases said defenses would remain unchanged. In another measure, Gallup found that 68 percent of the registered voters it interviewed had heard of the Pledge of Allegiance issue, and by a 2-1 margin they had a less favorable view of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> because of it. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in what has become a repeated refrain, has criticized <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for vetoing legislation in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> requiring teachers to lead classes in the Pledge. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he acted on the basis of a court opinion that the law was unconstitutional, and he accused <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> of impugning his patriotism. But 70 percent in the CBS-Times poll said teachers should be required to lead pupils in the pledge. And half of that group said it should be mandated even if the courts ruled the requirement unconstitutional. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also has been stressing environmental issues, traditionally a strong suit for Democrats, and the <ORGANIZATION> CBS-Times </ORGANIZATION> poll found him ranked nearly evenly with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on protecting the environment. The CBS-Times poll even found backing for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on an issue <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had sought to make his own: competence. Fifty-one percent said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would be more competent at managing the federal government, to 32 percent for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. Overall, the Gallup survey found 40 percent expressing an unfavorable view of <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, up from 32 percent three weeks ago and the highest all year for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in Gallup's poll. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was rated favorably by more voters, 53 percent, but <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> bettered him in both ratings, with 59 percent favorable and 35 percent unfavorable. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' confidence rating suffered in the CBS-Times poll, but in that measure <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s score worsened as well. Fifty-nine percent said they would be uneasy with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in an international crisis, up from 53 percent just after the Republican convention last month. Fewer _ 47 percent _ said they would be uneasy with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in a crisis, but that was up 10 points from the post-convention poll. Also, 45 percent said they would be confident with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, down from 51 percent; for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, 28 percent expressed confidence, little changed from 29 percent. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> continued to lead <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on one other key issue: Forty-seven percent said the Democrat would do more to help the middle class, while 33 percent picked <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. Finally, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> encountered a low rating on his choice of Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> as his running mate. Fifty-eight percent said they would be worried about <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> stepping in as president if something happened to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, and just 32 percent said <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> was qualified to serve as president. The CBS-Times poll was conducted among 1,043 probably voters from Thursday through Sunday and had a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage points. The Gallup poll was done Friday through Sunday among 1,003 registered voters and was given a four-point margin of error.
