<HEAD>Iraqi Official Says Some Kurds Must Be Resettled</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-UN-Kurds, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A high-ranking official said Tuesday that <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> is moving many Kurds from small villages for security or better services, but insisted it is not trying to wipe them out or change their style of life. Kurdish rebel groups and others have denounced <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s policy of demolishing small villages and relocating their population. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> suggested on Friday such acts were connected with `` genocide'' against the Kurdish people. But the official, <PERSON> Nizar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamdoon </PERSON>, deputy foreign secretary and former <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> ambassador to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said in an interview that the government has no intention `` to change the life of the Kurds.'' Asked about reports of widespread relocations, he said: `` If you're talking about the border area, the reasons are mainly security reasons, so that -LRB- rebel -RRB- infiltration stops. `` With development ... it's more feasible to bring people together to provide better services.'' <PERSON> Hamdoon </PERSON> said some of the Kurdish rebels who were offered amnesty after fleeing to <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> would be relocated if they return. `` Obviously, for security reasons we have to relocate some of them ... but they will be provided with a place within <LOCATION> Kurdistan </LOCATION>,'' he said, refering to the remote northern region of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> where Kurds live. Following a round of fighting that ended in 1975, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> demolished a string of villages along its border with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and moved their people. Over the last year, Baghdad-based diplomats said the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> army demolished scores of other small villages in the mountainous Kurdish territories and moved the people into towns or new concrete apartment blocks along main roads. The diplomat