<HEAD>Sailor Leaner After Ordeal, But Will Sail Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EUREKA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seventy-five days after he set sail, and 44 days after he was reported missing at sea, <PERSON> Donovan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> returned to dry land Tuesday with new respect for canned food and the Coast Guard. The 58-year-old <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, man had planned to sail his 32-foot wooden sloop from <LOCATION> Marina </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rey </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Oahu </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. He left in late June expecting to arrive by late July. `` I'm not an old salt or anything like that, but I'm not a novice,'' he said. On July 31, his family reported him missing. `` I'm married, but I did tell my wife before I left not to call the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>. I told her it takes a long time to get anywhere,'' he said during a telephone interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> minutes after he reached land here in northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` I have n't called her yet.'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' plans went astray shortly after he left. He headed south, then turned west at 16 degrees north latitude to swing over toward <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. `` And then a storm came along and blew me south and to the west of <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>,'' he said. Because of prevailing wind patterns, `` I could n't come back -LRB- northeast -RRB- to <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> against the wind, so I decided to come back to the mainland.'' With his radio batteries dead, he slowly worked his way through a small stock of canned food and vitamins. He dragged a line in hopes of catching fish, but `` I guess I'm not much of a fisherman.'' He had n't had a chance to weigh himself yet, but guessed he lost 20 to 25 pounds. Early Sunday, when he was just 100 miles off <LOCATION> Eureka </LOCATION>, a large storm came up and ripped away his hatch cover. `` Everything was in a shambles inside and I was having a hard time keeping the water out,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. Then another sailboat came along and called the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> on its radio. A <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> helicopter flew out a portable generator to power <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' radio and some rations. Then a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> boat towed him into <LOCATION> Humboldt </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> was really wonderful, and I ca n't say enough about them,'' said <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>. He is n't ready to give up sailing just because of one misadventure. `` I love the sea, and this has n't changed me so far as I want to give it up,'' he said. `` I feel healthier since I've sailed. Life in the city is n't good for you.''
