<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> questioned on Tuesday whether <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> rival <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is up to dealing with Soviet leaders at a time when Soviet economic difficulties offer great opportunities for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been around <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for a long time, but if he could n't stand up to the ayatollah or say ` no' to -LRB- Panamanian Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, how will he measure up to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>?'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` And if he truly believes that <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> is qualified to be one heartbeat away from the presidency, how can we trust his judgment when <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s future is on the line,'' he said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spoke to the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on Foreign Relations in what campaign aides described as a major address outlining his view of U.S.-Soviet relations. It was part of a week devoted largely to national security issues by the Democratic presidential nominee, who is trying to counter the Republicans' depiction of him as soft on defense. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> intensified that effort later at a General Dynamics tank facility in <LOCATION> Sterling </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, where he donned a helmet and rode in a M-1 <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> tank, the military's top battlefield tank, and pledged to make strengthening conventional weapons among his top defense priorities. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> stood through the hatch of the tank, his hand resting on a 7.62 mm machine gun, the tank's turret and cannon spinning, as the tank was driven at high speed around a grassy field. He said the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration had tried to cut tank production by one-quarter and asserted that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would cut conventional military spending to finance the Star Wars nuclear defense program. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> planned to address defense and weapons in a speech Wednesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Aides scheduled a stop in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> park, to view fire damage, on his way to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Thursday. In his <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> speech, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said the next president must `` seize the intiative'' in dealing with the Soviets. However, he said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` has no strategy for testing the limits of what is called ` new thinking' in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' He said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> under <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has an economy facing difficulty in providing for its people and that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> wants access to Western technology, resources and trade. `` Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> wants to make his country part of the international economic community,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` What is he prepared to do in return? Will we allow him to pursue that strategy unchallenged, or will we have a strategy of our own to rotect <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> interests and translate Soviet economic weakness into improved Soviet behavior in world affairs?'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he would deal firmly with the Soviets and said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is a Leninist who `` has not abandoned Soviet goals.'' He said, `` It would be naive to take <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> at his word, but it would be dangerous to allow his words to go unanswered.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he would challenge the Soviets to reduce European troops, cool regional conflicts, end the spread of nuclear and chemical weapons and missiles, reject terrorism and allow the emigration of Jews and other minorities. `` Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> must understand that if there is to be a fundamental change in the relationship of his country with the Western world, there must first be a fundamental change in the balance of forces in central <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. He said he wanted to build on the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces reduction agreement and would challenge <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to eliminate a Soviet advantage in tanks and artillery in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, `` not just by demobilizing those weapons but by destroying them.'' He also said he would seek to have the Soviets withdraw troops `` back into the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> hammered at his theme that Sen. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s running mate, was not up to dealing forcefully with the Soviets. He noted that three vice presidents since 1945 have been propelled suddenly to the presidency and that all of them later met as president with Soviet leaders. `` <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> is no <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` He's no <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. And he sure ai n't <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Truman </PERSON>. Can we stake our future on the hope that he is a match for <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>?'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> wrapped up the day in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, where in a speech to the Congressional Hispanic Caucus he said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s appointment of a Hispanic, <PERSON> Lauro </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON>, to Secretary of Education, was too little too late. `` For some people it's enough to wake up after eight years and create opportunity for one Hispanic,'' he said. `` I want to stand with you and create opportunity for 20 million Hispanics.''
