<HEAD>Woerner Warns Against Dropping Guard, Sees Larger European Role In
NATO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> Secretary General <PERSON> Manfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> said on Tuesday that Western Europeans will have to spend more for defense to avert a trans-Atlantic `` slanging match'' between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its allies. <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON>, in his first public speech since taking over as top political official of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, said he welcomed Soviet reforms, but doubted they would `` go far enough.'' `` We must take account of realities more than intentions,'' <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, a private organization. `` Soviet defense programs have not slowed down.'' But he added, `` I see more opportunities than risks ahead.'' The <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies should challenge Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> to make more progress toward military stability in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, a global ban on chemical weapons, greater observation of human rights and deeper economic and scientific cooperation. `` The success of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> is the driving force behind the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leadership's reforms, political as well as economic, but it is doubtful that they go far enough to overcome the structural failings of the Soviet system,'' <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> said. `` All this underscores just how wrong, indeed dangerous, it would be for the alliance to take a leap of faith and to let down its guard,'' said <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> who had been the West German defense minister before taking the alliance post last July 1. <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> said the issue of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> assuming a larger share of the common defense burden had been a central theme in his first discussions with European leaders, and `` they are committed to an equitable sharing of responsibility for collective defense,'' he said. `` The burden-sharing debate must not be allowed to degenerate into a numbers game or a trans-Atlantic slanging match,'' he said. <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> said he would work for `` a stronger European pillar within the alliance'' but added that it was essential for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> to remain committed to the defense of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. He said the allies should expand their cooperation outside the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> area, an idea that has encountered resistance in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` The Europeans and Canadians do not have the same kind of superpower responsibilities as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but they do have a global role,'' <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> said, citing examples such as providing aid to the Third World, thwarting Libyan aggression in <LOCATION> Chad </LOCATION> and patrolling the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Woerner </PERSON> met for nearly three hours on Tuesday with <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> and discussed the `` full range of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> issues,'' a <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said. He is to meet with other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials this week, including President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on Friday.
