<HEAD>Opposition Denounces Banning of TV Spot on Torture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Opposition leaders on Tuesday denounced the banning of an anti-government campaign commercial describing alleged torture by President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s secret police. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, meanwhile, ordered the cancellation of a pro-government television advertisement scheduled for Tuesday to make up for the banning of the opposition's Monday night spot. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, the 72-year-old army commander who seized power in a 1973 military coup, faces a national referendum Oct. 5 on a proposed eight more years of rule. According to government-approved rules for the campaign, his backers and opponents each receive 15 minutes of free television time nightly. On Monday night, only the pro-Pinochet spot was aired. The national television censorship board had objected to a one-minute, 55-second segment of the opposition's advertisement that quoted a federal judge investigating alleged cases of torture by the secret police. Opposition leaders said Wednesday the board offered to let them substitute a different segment, but they refused. The board then decided to bar airing of the entire 15-minute spot. `` We do n't accept censorship,'' Socialist <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagos </PERSON>, co-leader of a 16-party opposition coalition, told a news conference Tuesday. `` What happened last night helps to remind us that we are facing a dictator, and not in a fair electoral battle.'' <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaldivar </PERSON>, a Christian Democrat also leading the coalition, said: `` It's a dictator's action.'' The absence of the opposition ad sparked pot-banging and other demonstrations of anti-government sentiment around <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>, especially in working-class neighborhoods. `` <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> made a big mistake,'' <PERSON> Zaldivar </PERSON> said. `` In trying to do us damage, he created a reaction in the people that is overwhelmingly in our favor.'' <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> Lustig </PERSON>, executive secretary of the censorship board, called the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, said it objected to the segment because `` it attempted to involve the judicial power in a political campaign.'' He said at a news conference that the council had consulted the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, which said it had not authorized the judge's remarks. The judge, <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, was quoted in the advertisement as saying he is investigating cases of torture involving more than 50 people arrested by the secret police agency, called the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, known by its Spanish acronym, the <ORGANIZATION> CNI </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is duly established that they were arrested by <ORGANIZATION> CNI </ORGANIZATION> agents, that they were tortured by <ORGANIZATION> CNI </ORGANIZATION> agents, in <ORGANIZATION> CNI </ORGANIZATION> jails,'' <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> declares in the segment. The segment was extracted from a television interview <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> gave months ago, apparently to a foreign network. In March, he was told by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to stop speaking publicly about the cases. <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION> said the segment had been broadcast in at least 15 other countries. `` I ask why they refuse to let Chileans see what a Chilean judge has said, and which can be seen in the rest of the world?'' he said. <PERSON> Orlando </PERSON> <PERSON> Poblete </PERSON>, the Cabinet-rank government general secretary, told reporters that on Tuesday night only the opposition's 15-minute time slot would be broadcast The pro-government spot was being canceled at <ORGANIZATION> Pinochet </ORGANIZATION>'s order to keep the campaign fair, he said. If a majority vote yes in the plebiscite, <ORGANIZATION> Pinochet </ORGANIZATION> will remain president until 1997. If most voters reject him, open elections will be held in a year and he will hand over power to the winner in 1990. The government ordered free television time, from 10:45 p.m. to 11:15 p.m. each weeknight and at mid-day on weekends, starting Sept. 5 and ending Oct. 1. Besides the 15 minutes of free time, paid pro-government advertisements appear several times daily on all TV channels. The opposition says it can not afford paid ads, and doubts that the channels would allow them. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> toppled the elected government of President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON> and took power Sept. 11, 1973. <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, a Marxist, died in the takeover.
