<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 18 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>INDIANAPOLIS: 14-year-old stepdaughter.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The chemical castration, part of a sentence that included a year in prison and four years' probation, involved taking Depo-Provera, an experimental <ORGANIZATION> Upjohn </ORGANIZATION> drug used to reduce male sex drive. Such debates are n't new. In 1942, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> struck down an <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> law allowing sterilization of certain groups of felons, noting that `` marriage and procreation are fundamental to the very existence and survival of the race. ... In evil or reckless hands it can cause races or types which are inimical to the dominant group to wither and disappear.'' And similar language is being used today. `` I do n't understand where any court in this country is qualified to tell people ... who's fit to breed and who is n't,'' said <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> public defender representing the woman originally sentenced to birth control. `` It does n't take a huge jump from Who can have children? to Whose life is meaningful and whose is n't?'' he said. `` These are questions the law is n't capable of answering.'' But others argue alternative sentences can be effective. `` We have a very, very destructive system,'' said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Polsby </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> law professor. `` We send too many people down the river. We've got to be more creative. -LRB- If there are -RRB- people that you can handle in some other way, handle them in some other way.'' And although <PERSON> Polsby </PERSON> agreed with the need to protect rights, he said, `` 20 years of close confinement in a penitentiary is as serious a deprivation of civil liberties as you can imagine, short of being killed.'' That's a good possibility for Miss <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON>, a 29-year-old unemployed waitress with a history of emotional problems and self-abuse. Last summer, while awaiting trial, Miss <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> injected urine in her breasts, a bizarre act <PERSON> Donahoe </PERSON> said stemmed from frustration and depression. Many years ago, he said, she nicked her wrists with a razor. Miss <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON>'s behavior was scrutinized shortly after <PERSON> Joshua </PERSON>'s birth when medical workers noticed the baby's repeated coughing, vomiting and breathing difficulties occurred only when his mother was alone with him <PERSON> Donahoe </PERSON> said the boy was placed in a foster home but was returned to his mother several weeks later when suspicions of abuse could not be proven. On Aug. 28, 1986, <PERSON> Joshua </PERSON> was hospitalized with a cough. Five days later, after improving steadily, he suddenly grew lethargic; he was in a coma by the next morning. On Sept. 5, life support was turned off. An autopsy found he had died from drugs likely given within 24 hours of cardiac arrest, which caused his brain death. The drugs, specifically an anti-depressant and an anti-psychotic, were dispensed to his mother. Originally, prosecutors claimed Miss <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> turned off an alarm on a monitor that would have alerted nurses to <PERSON> Joshua </PERSON>'s sudden change in brain activity. She denied the allegation, and it was dropped from the final charges before the plea agreement. The accusation was mirrored this summer when a doctor said <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> disconnected a tube providing nourishment to her and her fetus. <PERSON> Donahoe </PERSON> said his client was having trouble keeping food down, but attorney <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Bookwalter </PERSON>, representing the fetus, said Miss <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> engaged in self-induced vomiting `` to create a medical calamity involving the unborn child.'' `` She's killed one -LRB- child -RRB- purposely,'' he said. `` She has tried to cause a premature birth of a second one. Anybody who does n't think she was trying ... to harm the two would have to be crazy. <PERSON> Donahoe </PERSON> disagrees. `` I really believe, more than anyone on this planet, she wants to bring a healthy baby into this world,'' he said. `` There might be a connection between that need ... and what she's been convicted of.'' Whatever she chooses, <PERSON> Donahoe </PERSON> says her future is bleak. The idea of sterilization `` makes her feel like she's being treated like an animal,'' he said, and if she's imprisoned, `` being kept in a cage is being kept like an animal. Her dilemma is how she's going to be treated like an animal.''
</TEXT>
