<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> expects its first quarter operating income to be flat, due to continued sluggish sales by its Burger King fast-food restaurant chain, the company's chairman said Tuesday. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, in his first major public appearance as the food and restaurant company's new chairman, told <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s annual meeting that comparable Burger King restaurant sales were off 2 percent in the first quarter of fiscal 1989 from the same period last year. The decline extended a trend that contributed to a major restructuring in the previous year, which sharply reduced <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s net earnings. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> had net earnings in fiscal 1988 of $ 69.3 million, or 81 cents a share, compared with $ 181.9 million, or $ 2.10 a share in fiscal 1987. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said that for the first quarter of fiscal 1989 operating results should be `` virtually flat'' although net income will be up about 25 percent because of a one-time benefit in deferred taxes. `` Foods will have an excellent first quarter, but restaurants, as I indicated, will be down because of the investment expenses we are incurring and because of continued sluggish sales at Burger King,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. Besides spending $ 30 million this year to upgrade training and add new managerial staff at <LOCATION> Burger </LOCATION> <LOCATION> King </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> will begin a $ 150 million capital improvement plan to add 60 new company stores and upgrade existing stores, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` The long-term profit performance for the whole company makes it essential that we succeed, and there is no reason why we can not,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` I will be present in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> at our Burger King headquarters frequently to provide encouragement and to assist in making the right judgments with a clear sense of urgency.'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said he expects profit growth in the foods division during the coming fiscal years and an overall `` solid financial gain'' despite the expenses incurred to improve restaurant sales. He said the company's <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> A </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Restaurant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which operates the full-service chains of Steak and Ale and <PERSON> Bennigan </PERSON>'s, experienced its first upturn in average restaurant sales in four years during the first quarter of this year. In last year's restructuring, the subsidiary dropped two small chains, got out of the hotel food service business and closed 23 underperforming Steak and Ale restaurants.
