<HEAD>House Members Scrutinize Plan To Give Banks New Securities Power</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subcommittee hearing begins 10 a.m. EDT; tops uncertain. A
version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> wary of granting banks new securities powers are marshaling evidence to back their position by looking at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks' overseas operations. Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mich </LOCATION>., called a meeting of his <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> oversight subcommittee today to review a <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> report suggesting banks may have problems handling new powers Although banks are barred from most securities activities in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> rules permit bank subsidiaries to trade and underwrite securities abroad. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, at the request of Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., looked at how large <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks with European operations fared in the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> markets in 1986 and 1987 `` Bank examination reports ... indicate that most of the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> securities subsidiaries of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks recorded losses or were marginally profitable,'' the report said, noting that the problems were made worse by the world stock market crash in October 1987. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> attributed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks' poor showing in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in part to `` significant management and internal control problems.'' However, it also took note of the turbulence of the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market, which recently had been deregulated by the British government. Eighteen of the 50 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks operating in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> engaged in at least some securities underwriting and dealing, the watchdog agency said. In several instances during the period of the crash, <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> securities subsidiaries were forced to call on their parent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks for infusions of capital to make up for losses, it said. `` This study foreshadows the threat to our banking system if banks are allowed unfettered entry into our domestic securities markets,'' said <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> finance subcommittee. <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> are using the study in their efforts to counter bills that would repeal or substantially alter the 1933 Glass-Steagall Act, which separated commercial and investment banking in the wake of the 1929 stock market crash and subsequent wave of bank failures. Bills granting banks new securities powers have passed the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The legislation must be reviewed by <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>'s committee before the full House can act. Both <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> have expressed skepticism about relaxing the Glass-Steagall barriers. In a television interview over the weekend, <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> said `` if I have any say'' such legislation will not be enacted this year.
</TEXT>
