<HEAD>Report Says Taiwan Planning To Cut More Tariffs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> plans to cut import tariffs on several additional products, including mineral oils and cooling equipment, to help reduce trade friction with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, a newspaper reported Tuesday. The widely circulated <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> quoted unidentified financial officials as saying <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> would lower tariffs on the 56 `` competitive <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> products to effectively ease trade tension'' between <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and its chief trading partner. For each of the 56 items, U.S.-made products currently make up more than 20 percent of <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s imports of that item, the newspaper said. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Fu-jen </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> official, declined to comment on the newspaper report. Last month, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> announced it would cut import tariffs on 335 other items later this month. The newspaper said tariffs would be cut for 52 of the 175 items for which <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiators requested reductions during trade talks in April. However, tariffs will be cut for only two of the 102 agricultural items requested by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> side because Taiwanese officials believe local farmers need protection, the newspaper said. The new items include broth, mineral oils, compressors and cooling equipment, it said. In February, tariffs on 3,500 items were cut by an average of 50 percent in <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s most sweeping tariff cuts. <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> has been under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pressure to reduce its large bilateral trade surplus. Trade between <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last year totaled $ 31.2 billion, with <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s exports exceeding imports by $ 16 billion. During the first eight months of this year, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s imports from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> totaled $ 9.3 billion, up 102 percent from a year earlier. Its bilateral trade surplus totaled $ 6.4 billion during the period.
