<HEAD>Inflation, Labor Shortage Troubling Financial Secretary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Inflation and labor shortages are two major economic problems facing <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, Financial Secretary Piers <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> said Tuesday. <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON>, in an evaluation of the economy's performance, also slightly revised his projection of this year's growth rate to 6 percent from 5 percent, still well below the 13.5 percent rate for 1987. Interest rate increases in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the slower economic growth worldwide are contributing factors in the decline in growth of the British colony's export-fueled economy, he said. <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> noted, however, that the local economy `` is still operating close to capacity, so that inflation and labor shortages continue to be our two major concerns.'' He said the inflation rate was expected to hit 7.5 percent this year, slightly higher than previously projected. The unemployment rate, 1.8 percent in June, has reached historic lows, resulting in rapid increases of wages and salaries, <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> added. The government is considering easing a ban on the import of foreign labor because of the widespread labor shortages, but <PERSON> Jacobs </PERSON> did not say whether he favored such a move.
