ling 11 percent in the last three years. Officials said the ratified contract reflected an improved offer by DAW and W-I. As a result of the settlement, the unions asked the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> to drop an unfair labor practice charge against the two companies, officials said. The strike began June 6 and affected dozens of logging operations and lumber mills in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. The unions demanded increases in basic wage rates to restore cuts accepted two years ago, when the companies sought concessions to withstand a recession in the industry. But the companies balked, offering annual bonuses and production incentives instead. The weekend settlement affects DAW plants in Bend and <LOCATION> Redmond </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Coeur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> d'Alene </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Albeni </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>; and Superior, <PERSON> Mont </PERSON>. W-I mills affected are in <ORGANIZATION> Coeur </ORGANIZATION> d' <PERSON> Alene </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Sandpoint </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. All the plants reopened Monday except the one at <LOCATION> Sandpoint </LOCATION>, which remained closed while air-quality questions were worked out with local officials.
