<HEAD>Chain Ponders Restructuring After Hafts Get OK to Buy Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said today it was exploring a $ 3.77 billion defensive restructuring that would plunge the supermarket giant into debt and force it to sell assets after the <PERSON> Haft </PERSON> family, well known for hostile takeover attempts, won federal clearance to acquire a chunk of the company. The nation's largest grocery chain, which operates more than 1,300 supermarkets, 900 convenience stores and other operations in 29 states, said in a statement that the possible restructuring was prompted partly by `` the high level of takeover and restructuring activity involving supermarket companies.'' The statement also mentioned a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> ruling Friday that allows the <ORGANIZATION> Hafts </ORGANIZATION>, a Maryland-based clan of corporate takeover strategists who have unsuccessfully chased other supermarket chains but made huge profits in the process, to acquire at least $ 15 million worth of <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> stock. <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> said the restructuring would involve substantial but unspecified bank loans, pay shareholders $ 48 in cash and securities per share and allow them to keep their stock. <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> has about 78.57 million shares outstanding. `` The substantial debt would be repaid from cash flow from operations, disposition of non-core and underproductive assets, significant reduction in capital expenditures and reduced expenses,'' <PERSON> Lyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Everingham </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of the Cincinnati-based company, said in the statement. The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> ruling was the first official sign of the <ORGANIZATION> Hafts </ORGANIZATION>' interest in <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION>. But the commission's statement did not say how much <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> stock the <ORGANIZATION> Hafts </ORGANIZATION> want to buy. Representatives for the <ORGANIZATION> Hafts </ORGANIZATION> declined to comment. <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION>'s stock has traded heavily over the past five months partly because of rumors that the <ORGANIZATION> Hafts </ORGANIZATION> and other potential acquirers were interested in the company. News of the commission's decision started circulating Friday, sending <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION>'s stock up $ 1.25 in heavy trading to close at $ 38 a share. On Monday the company's stock closed up another $ 1.50 at $ 39.50, also on heavy trading. One analyst predicted that the <ORGANIZATION> Hafts </ORGANIZATION> would likely break up Kroger if they purchased it. `` It's almost certain that they'll start dismantling the company and selling off its assets,'' said <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Giblen </PERSON>, vice president at <LOCATION> Rotan-Mosle </LOCATION>, a Houston-based subsidiary of the investment firm of <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. But, <PERSON> Giblen </PERSON> also said that <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Haft </PERSON> and his father, <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON>, who operate the <ORGANIZATION> Dart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Landover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, may be serious about running a grocery company. They demonstrated that earlier this spring, when they bought a small <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, grocery chain. Instead of selling it off for the cash, the <ORGANIZATION> Hafts </ORGANIZATION> are using the company to learn how to manage a grocery firm, <PERSON> Giblen </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Hafts </ORGANIZATION> have failed in their efforts to buy such companies as <ORGANIZATION> Safeway </ORGANIZATION>, Supermarkets General and <ORGANIZATION> Stop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Shop, but have made profits in selling stock shares back to those companies.
