<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stock market was lower in early trading today, recovering somewhat from its initial decline. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 4.62 points at 2,067.75 at 11 a.m. EDT, bouncing back from an early fall of 10.31 points. Declining issues outnumbered advances by around 7-to-4, with 696 issues down, 404 up and 497 unchanged. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> totaled 51.88 million shares. Activity was said to be dampened, as on Monday, by the observance of the Jewish New Year holiday. Analysts said the overall market was dragged down early in the session by negative news affecting shares of semiconductor companies, including <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s reported loss Monday of $ 30.5 million in its first fiscal quarter. National Semiconductor shares were down -RCB- at 8 -RRB-. `` That sent the whole group into a tailspin,'' said <PERSON> Hildegarde </PERSON> <PERSON> Zagorski </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The market continues to await Wednesday's government report on the nation's merchandise trade deficit for July. The announcement early today that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> current-account deficit shrank by 9.8 percent in the second quarter to $ 33.3 billion had little impact since it is a less recent reading of the trade picture. The current account is the broadest measure of a country's trade, while the July merchandise trade report will be a more narrow and recent indicator The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index of all its listed common stocks was down 0.26 at 150.37. At the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the market value index had slipped 0.73 to 295.94.
