<FIRST>a f BC-BugVac Adv17-18   09-13 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-BugVac, Adv 17-18,0769</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 17</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Sept. 17-18 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Zapping Those Bad Bugs With Vacuum Cleaner</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE BIGHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A contraption that sucks bad bugs off strawberry plants may become a handy tool for farmers in the drive to kill pests without using so many chemicals. Three farming members of <ORGANIZATION> Driscoll </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strawberry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Watsonville </LOCATION>, in northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, are using a company-designed machine called a BugVac this year to vacuum lygus bugs off their plants. The custom-made vacuum machine, mounted on a tractor, moves down rows of young berries, providing just enough suction to zap lygus bugs that like to live near the top of the plants. Beneficial insects that live lower on the plants are not disturbed by the machine, explained <PERSON> Driscoll </PERSON> researcher Ed Show. <PERSON> Green </PERSON> leaves and the ripening fruit also are left unharmed. Show adapted the idea from a hand vacuum the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> developed years ago to test the levels of insect populations. The researcher's innovation consists of hydraulically driven fans and suction hoses. `` The vacuum does n't deep clean the whole strawberry plant,'' Show said in an interview. `` We're affecting only the bugs on the top part of the plant. It will suck up and remove bugs of all kinds, the good and the bad, but it's not as detrimental to the beneficial insect community.'' Perhaps the main benefit from the BugVac is saving the beneficial insects needed to eat other damaging bugs such as western spider mites, which have become resistant to pesticides. `` We have no effective miticides to control spider mites, so if we spray for lygus bugs, we create a real spider mite problem because we knock out the beneficial insects,'' Show says. Vacuum cleaning the plants does not eliminate as many lygus bugs as spraying them with pesticides would. However, growers who tried the new technique were able to keep the lygus bug population close to or slightly below what is termed the economic threshold in integrated pest management _ the level at which the pest population causes financial losses. `` We're learning how many lygus bugs we can get away with in a field,'' Show said. The board of <ORGANIZATION> Driscoll </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, which provides its own patented strawberry varieties to affiliated growers, asked Show to find ways to reduce or eliminate as much use of pesticides as possible because of increasing regulatory restrictions, increasing resistance by bugs to some chemicals and doubts about whether adequate new chemicals will become available. Show decided to adapt the DVac machine, a hand-held or backpack device used to suck up small numbers of pests in estimating how badly a field is infested. `` Given that basic idea, we built a prototype on bicycle wheels, pushed it through test plots and found it could catch what seemed like an impressive number of lygus bugs,'' Show said. This was the first season growers used Show's device commercially, and the three who had machines built seem satisfied with the results. Reiter Affiliated of <LOCATION> Watsonville </LOCATION> used a BugVac on 71 acres of strawberries at <LOCATION> Salinas </LOCATION>, about 125 miles south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, and plans to have two more machines built for use on all of the company's 225 acres next year. General manager <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> estimates the vacuum machine saved $ 100 - $ 200 an acre over the cost of pesticides, and owner <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> <PERSON> Reiter </PERSON> said the savings may even be higher `` It's been a real good deal for us,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> McCluney </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Watsonville </LOCATION>, who manufactures the BugVacs, says he's now built nine or 10 and has orders for at least that many more with still other farmers considering the device. The cost of the machines runs between $ 12,000 and $ 17,000. `` It definitely does work under most circumstances when properly used with integrated pest management and other methods,'' <PERSON> McCluney </PERSON> said. `` It's not just a replacement for a spray tractor but needs to be in conjunction with predator releases.'' Use of the BugVac may spread from strawberries to other <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> vegetables, such as lettuce. `` There's interest on the part of some other vegetable growers,'' said Show, adding that he has heard of at least one <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> farmer who uses a similar apparatus to control potato beetles. <PERSON> McCluney </PERSON> said he plans a trip to <PERSON> Brawley </PERSON> in southeastern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> `` to see if we can use this new idea to help out with their white fly problem.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Sept. 17-18</NOTE>
