<HEAD>Corn, Soybeans Open Lower; Wheat Rallies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Corn and soybean futures opened lower today on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> while wheat traded higher, all in reaction to Monday's crop production report from <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The government's new harvest projections of 4.46 billion bushels of corn and 1.47 billion bushels of soybeans were higher than the market had expected, prompting many players to sell contracts for future delivery of those commodities, analysts said. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s wheat production number _ 1.81 billion bushels _ also was higher than expected. But its bearish implications were more than offset by new government predictions of lower grain production in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, and a forecast for increased grain imports by the Soviets. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is negotiating a new long-term agreement to supply grain to the Soviets. Demand concerns have replaced supply fears as the main influence on crop futures prices and will continue to dominate trading as the corn and soybean harvest progresses, said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>, grain specialist with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` The key is how is the demand going to respond, when are the spurts of business going to come, how is the market going to handle the fact that over the next 60 days we are going to be harvesting and maximizing the supply side in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>,'' he said. In early trading, wheat was 3 \ cents to 6 cents higher with the contract for delivery in September at $ 4.08 a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to 1 -RCB- cents higher with September at $ 2.85 a bushel; oats were -LCB- cent to 2 -LCB- cents higher with December at $ 2.75 a bushel; soybeans were 1 -LCB- cents to 8 cents lower with September at $ 8.66 a bushel Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were higher in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .22 cent to .48 cent higher with October at 70.10 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .50 cent lower to .05 cent higher with September at 79.15 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent to .68 cent higher with October at 38.40 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .08 cent to 1.23 cents higher with February at 47.50 cents a pound. Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Monday.
