<FIRST>a f BC-Fine-TunedSteel Adv17-18   09-13 0951</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Fine-Tuned Steel, Adv 17-18,0977</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 17</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Sept. 17-18 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Fine Tuning for High Strength, Japan Leading The Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After learning from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> about modern furnaces, enlightened labor relations and customer service, American steelmakers are once again looking across the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> _ this time for a steel process that may help protect <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships at sea and tanks on land. High-strength, low-alloy steel plate _ easier to weld, less dependent on hard-to-get alloying elements and potentially cheaper to make _ is the latest fruit of the Japanese industrial system. `` It's the wave of the future,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Null </PERSON>, head of the metals branch of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s Sea Systems Command. American steelmakers lag <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> by 10 to 15 years in the computer-controlled processing needed to make the super-tough steel. But the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> is anxious to catch up. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> wants to build ships out of world-class steel. They want the best that money can buy, and they're willing to pay for it,'' said <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> McHenry </PERSON>, a steel specialist for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>, formerly the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Standards </ORGANIZATION>. `` But right now, the American steel plate producers do n't have all the technical tools available to them,'' <PERSON> McHenry </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from his <LOCATION> Boulder </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, office. Besides the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s support, the Army is interested in the new plate for its armored vehicles. The material has applications in commercial shipping as well. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> hopes to win its request for $ 5.5 million in the 1989 defense budget to send American steel to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for processing and to bring it back for testing. If the plate meets specifications and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> appropriates more money, the department would negotiate with domestic steel companies for one of them to upgrade a plate mill with the new technology in exchange for guaranteed sales. `` We're very excited about this project. I think it has a great deal of potential for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steel industry,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Corridore </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> industrial specialist who heads the program. <PERSON> McHenry </PERSON> said the reasons American steelmakers lag the Japanese in this area are intertwined with the forces that helped undermine <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s postwar industrial power. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> steelmakers invested early on in research that led to computerized processing, the key to more precise manipulating of steel's metallurgical properties as the metal is heated, cooled, squeezed and stretched. By 1983, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s five major plate makers were using controlled cooling, which helps reduce the need for alloying steel with niobium, molybdenum and other elements that make the finished plates tricky to weld. It's the heart of the technology the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> is willing to pay American steelmakers to adopt. It is a follow-up technology to controlled rolling, which the Japanese commercialized in the late 1960s. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> adopted that in the 1980s, <PERSON> McHenry </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think the industry is being stubborn or hard-headed or ignorant by not adopting this technology,'' <PERSON> McHenry </PERSON> said. `` The technology is not that attractive from a commercial standpoint.'' `` We're not stupid in this country despite what you read,'' said <PERSON> Marshal </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazur </PERSON>, manager of government programs for <ORGANIZATION> Bethlehem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a leading plate maker. `` We've been aware of this technology for a long time. But we're a free market economy, and we do n't always have access to all the capital that you need to invest in technology `` That situation has n't always presented itself to our trading partners, so it's real easy for the Japanese with easy access to capital to go down their wish list and made a decision to proceed,'' <PERSON> Mazur </PERSON> said. Without government underwriting, `` there's no way you can justify putting these units in,'' said <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Ardo </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Basic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Processing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Ardo </PERSON>, however, is not a fan of the new Japanese technology and thinks the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> should be looking to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> labs for help. `` I think the Pentagon has been sold a bill of goods on this,'' he said. `` But I give them the benefit of the doubt. They really believe they're doing something that's correct.'' <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Ardo </PERSON> said Japanese steelmakers `` have shown the benefits of accelerated cooling to much of our military, and there's no question that what they're saying is true. It's just that I think our steel industry needs many things to benefit the military before they get to an accelerated cooling unit.'' Controlled cooling, also called accelerated cooling, involves computers calculating exactly when to spray water on a hot plate as it emerges in its final shape from a rolling mill. `` But it's not that simple,'' said <PERSON> McHenry </PERSON>, who recommended high-strength, low-alloy steel to the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> after studying the new process for a year in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` The computer ... controls when the cooling starts and when the cooling stops, what the volume of water is, what the distribution of water is from side to side and what the rate of travel of the plate through this shower is,'' he said. The Japanese coupled that technique to direct rolling, in which molten steel is cast into 8-inch thick slabs, then rolled directly into plate an inch or so thick. The method eliminates the time - and energy-consuming steps of cooling the slabs to room temperature to be inspected, cleaned of surface defects and reheated It is possible only with steel of precise and consistent composition, itself a benefit of computer-controlled furnaces. Together, those processes allow for reductions in alloying elements, including chromium and vanadium which the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> control. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> developed the processes to supply to its busy fabricators, who produce off-shore drilling platforms and transcontinental pipelines.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Sept. 17-18</NOTE>
