<HEAD>Former Rolm Head Announcing New Computer Network</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Oshman </PERSON> and other former executives of <ORGANIZATION> Rolm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> now at <ORGANIZATION> Ultra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> are introducing a product <PERSON> Oshman </PERSON> says will revolutionize the world of high-speed computer networks. `` It is, in a real sense, uncharted waters,'' <PERSON> Oshman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ultra </PERSON>'s chairman, said Monday of the new network being unveiled next Tuesday Ultra's system, which already has won endorsements from several makers of a new generation of so-called mini-supercomputers, is essentially a local area network that passes information among computers at a theoretical maximum rate of 1 billion bits per second. Ultra can transfer the contents of an encyclopedia in a few seconds, 100 times faster than one widely used network for office computers. Supercomputers need faster local area networks because computer speed has outpaced the ability of the machines to transfer information. `` Ultra has basically found a very fast way of allowing high-performance computers to talk to each other,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaffer </PERSON>, editor of <ORGANIZATION> Technologic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Letter </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` It is hot stuff.'' Several makers of high-speed computers have agreed to market the network and connect their machines to the system. <ORGANIZATION> Rolm </ORGANIZATION>, his former company, was sold to <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> in 1984.
