<FIRST>r f BC-Drought-Barges     09-13 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drought-Barges,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Execs: Drought Hurt River Barge Industry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Executives of river barge companies say this summer's drought stalled their efforts to recover from some lean years. After a severe recession in the early 1980s, when some barge lines merged and others went broke, the companies saw 1988 as the year to cap a comeback. But they have been unpleasantly surprised by mounting losses. `` Finally this year, people began to make money until <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Nature </PERSON> gave us a lousy deal,'' <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, vice president of the trade group <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Waterways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operators </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday. A study commissioned by the trade group projected the industry this year will suffer losses of as much as $ 200 million on revenue of $ 1 billion, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. Operating costs of barge companies have soared while many of the rates are fixed by long-term contracts, officials said. The barge industry struggled as a whole from 1982 to 1986, when an oversupply of barges depressed hauling rates. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had proposed several bills that would help the industry by tax deferrals or direct subsidies, but in August the industry announced it wanted no help, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. Commercial traffic on the dam-regulated <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> has continued without a hitch despite the summer drought, but shallow water in the lower <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> has tied up barges and $ 7,000-a-day towboats. Travel time for barges has doubled this summer. In addition, special drought restrictions reduced by half the number of barges that are allowed to be lashed together, requiring barge companies to use more tow boats. The restrictions also limit the load each barge can carry. `` A turnaround year turned into a real dumper,'' said <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Larson </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Merchants </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, where the price of barge transportation for grain is determined in trade. Slower travel and the smaller loads caused a shortage of barges and boats this summer, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hain </PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> M-G </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> barge company. `` It was difficult to quote prices because there were n't any barges available,'' he said. He said there was a substantial decline in company profits this summer. At <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, another Cincinnati-based line, profits will be down although the company will still make money, said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Frasher </PERSON>, vice president of operations. `` This -LRB- drought -RRB- was not needed at this time,'' <PERSON> Frasher </PERSON> said.
