Ld-Writethru; CORRECTS direction of oat trading in final graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crop futures prices closed mostly higher Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> as strength from the buoyant wheat market spilled over into the corn and soybean pits. Corn and soybean futures had opened lower in reaction to the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s higher-than-expected harvest estimates, issued after the close of trading on Monday. The report estimated 1988 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn production at 4.46 billion bushels and soybean production at 1.47 billion bushels. The numbers represent sharp declines from last year's production levels because of drought damage, but were still above most private forecasts. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s wheat-production estimate also was higher than expected but wheat futures prices rallied on the report's predictions of declining Soviet and Canadian wheat production and increasing Soviet grain imports Tuesday's market performance `` is a reflection of the fact that while everyone was focused on the disappointing numbers put out by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> domestically, the world numbers for wheat came out friendly,'' said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>, grain specialist with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. With potential crop-weather problems developing in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and severe crop losses a hard fact in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, `` the world situation is still tight'' for wheat, <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> said. At the close, wheat was 3 cents to 9 -RCB- cents higher with the contract for delivery in September at $ 4.11 a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to 2 -RCB- cents higher with September at $ 2.85 a bushel; oats were 2 cents to 3 -LCB- cents higher with September at $ 2.64 a bushel; soybeans were 5 -LCB- cents to 8 -LCB- cents higher with September at $ 8.76 a bushel.
