states., to UPDATE with final stock price.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BENTLEY BOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it was considering a $ 3.77 billion restructuring plan, but said the proposal was not specifically designed to ward off a possible hostile takeover bid by <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Haft </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION>, one of the nation's largest grocery chains, said it was asking its board of directors to approve a plan that would plunge the company into debt but keep it publicly owned. <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> has 1,300 supermarkets and other operations in 29 states. The announcement sent <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> stock soaring $ 11.75 a share to $ 51.25 in nationwide trading of issues listed on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. A <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> ruling on Friday allowed the <ORGANIZATION> Hafts </ORGANIZATION> to acquire at least $ 15 million worth of <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> stock. The Hafts, who control <ORGANIZATION> Dart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Landover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, are corporate takeover strategists and have unsuccessfully chased other supermarket chains but made huge profits in the process. `` This restructuring is not specifically tailored to the <PERSON> Haft </PERSON> situation,'' <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernish </PERSON> said. `` We take it seriously. But ever since the market became competitive in 1985 or 1986, we've been pretty vigilant about this. We want to keep <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> an independent and public company.'' <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> said the restructuring would involve substantial but unspecified bank loans, paying shareholders $ 48 in cash and securities per share and allowing them to keep their stock. <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> has about 78.57 million shares outstanding. <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> said it will repay the loans using cash flow from operations, reducing expenses and selling assets. In a 1986 restructuring, <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> sold its chain of SupeRx retail drugstores, and <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> has worked since July to sell off its unprofitable chain of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> Choice supermarkets and liquor stores in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. `` This is a case of extending that process,'' <PERSON> Bernish </PERSON> said. `` Our review of assets will be heightened if this plan is approved.'' The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> ruling was the first official sign of the <ORGANIZATION> Hafts </ORGANIZATION>' interest in <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> Representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> Hafts </ORGANIZATION> declined to comment. Supermarket industry analysts said the restructuring plan was a positive step for <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION>. `` This has been an option for <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> for a long time. It is not necessarily a response to the <PERSON> Haft </PERSON> announcement, but the <PERSON> Haft </PERSON> family move was a catalyst,'' said <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Shiels </PERSON>, analyst for the investment firm <PERSON> Hilliard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION> `` <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> has been looking for ways to reward its stockholders,'' she said. `` This restructuring allows the company to stay public ... This is a prudent move for <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION>.'' <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION>'s stock has traded heavily over the past five months, partly because of rumors the <ORGANIZATION> Hafts </ORGANIZATION> and other potential acquirers were interested in the company. If the <ORGANIZATION> Hafts </ORGANIZATION> were to take over <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION>, `` It's almost certain that they'll start dismantling the company and selling off its assets,'' said <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Giblen </PERSON>, vice president at <LOCATION> Rotan-Mosle </LOCATION>, a Houston-based investment firm. But <PERSON> Giblen </PERSON> also said the <ORGANIZATION> Hafts </ORGANIZATION> may be serious about running a grocery company. They demonstrated that earlier this spring when they bought a small <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, grocery chain. Instead of selling it off for the cash, the <ORGANIZATION> Hafts </ORGANIZATION> are using the company to learn how to manage a grocery firm, <PERSON> Giblen </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Hafts </ORGANIZATION> have failed in their efforts to buy such companies as <ORGANIZATION> Safeway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Supermarkets </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Stop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION> but have profited in selling stock back to those companies.
