<HEAD>Post Office Peace In Balance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Peace in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s two-week Post Office strike appeared in the balance Tuesday night as thousands of workers stayed off the job despite Monday's settlement of the dispute. It was still impossible to post a letter in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> where mail boxes remained sealed. The <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said work had begun on clearing 150 million letters and packages backed up in the system. Although it expected a full return to work by Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said it could be two weeks before service was restored to normal. As night shifts began, it estimated that 20,000 of the 100,000 strikers had returned to work. It said another 40,000 worked during the strike. <PERSON> Tuffin </PERSON>, general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>, said agreement was reached Monday on the issue of regional pay bonuses but the key issue of whether union members would allow casual workers to handle the mail backlog had been left to local negotiations. He said the union would back members remaining on strike if they could not agree terms on casual labor and overtime with Post Office local managers. The union said half the country's 15,000 sorting offices were still on strike and only six of the 82 major sorting centers were working. It said staff at <LOCATION> Glasgow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Hull </PERSON> had voted to stay out and similar decisions were expected at other offices. The strike began as a 24-hour walkout on Aug. 31 against the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> desire to pay bonuses to new workers in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and southeast <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> where the cost of living is high and retaining workers difficult. The union wanted the bonuses paid nationally. Strikes mushroomed Sept. 1 when the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> tried to bring in workers to clear the mail backlog. <PERSON> Tuffin </PERSON> said Monday the bonus system had been accepted until a new one could be worked out in about six weeks.
