$33.8 billion.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The government reported on Tuesday a sharp improvement in the broadest measure of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade from April through June, while stocks got a boost from predictions that the trade deficit would continue to decline. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the deficit in the current account shrank to $ 33.3 billion in the second quarter, a 9.8 percent improvement from a first quarter imbalance of $ 36.9 billion. It was the biggest quarterly improvement since a 20.1 percent drop in the final three months of last year. The current account covers not only trade in merchandise but also trade in services, which primarily reflect the flow of investment earnings between countries. On Wednesday, the government will report the merchandise trade balance for July, a monthly figure watched closely by the financial markets. The Dow Jones industrial average spurted ahead in late trading Tuesday, encouraged by remarks from <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary designate <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, who said at his <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> confirmation hearing that he expects the trade deficit to decline at a surprisingly fast pace over the next few years. The Dow Jones average of 30 blue-chip stocks ended 10.67 points higher at 2,083.04 after a mostly lackluster session. <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, an investment banker who investigated the causes of last year's stock market crash, was nominated by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to replace former <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. In other markets, the dollar strengthened slightly, but activity was slow in advance of the July trade figures. Bond prices gained as the yield on the government's 30-year issue slipped below 9 percent. Oil prices advanced, driven by a rise in wholesale gasoline prices, which soared on news that refineries and oil platforms were threatened by a hurricane approaching the Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The contract for October delivery of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, rose 7 cents to settle at $ 14.56 a 42-gallon barrel on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery closed up 1.19 cents at 43.81 cents a gallon. The government's trade report showed the second-quarter improvement in the current account deficit occurred because the deficit in merchandise trade fell to $ 29.9 billion, down from $ 35.2 billion in the first quarter, as exports rose to a record level and imports posted the first quarterly decline in three years. The good news was tempered by the fact that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> suffered its first deficit in three decades in the category that includes investment earnings. The report showed a $ 492 million imbalance in services, meaning that foreigners earned more on their investments during the quarter than Americans earned on overseas investments. Still, for the first six months of this year, the current account deficit has been running at an annual rate of $ 140.5 billion, a substantial improvement from a record deficit of $ 154 billion in 1987. The improvement has come about because of a boom in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports, reflecting declines in the value of the dollar since 1985 which have made American goods competitive once again on overseas markets. Also on Tuesday, the congressional <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> heard a panel of economists urge further action to cut federal budget deficits as a way of slowing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> domestic demand and further reducing the trade deficit. In other economic news, the government released a state-by-state report on unemployment in which <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> emerged as the best job provider for its residents. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> slipped from first place to 10th in the past year among states with the lowest unemployment rates.
