quest a new trial. <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> said oral arguments would be presented after attorneys had a chance to review the briefs. `` The appeal will take place after the post-trial activities, and we do anticipate being successful on appeal,'' <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Brosnahan </PERSON>, one of Mrs. <PERSON> Kociemba </PERSON>'s attorneys, said last Friday the case marked the first time a jury had awarded punitive damages against <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> for a Copper-7-related illness and also was the largest award. About 500 suits have been filed over the Copper-7, the most widely used IUD in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> before it was withdrawn from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market in January 1986 in the midst of litigation. Mrs. <PERSON> Kociemba </PERSON> had sought $ 15 million in punitive damages, $ 1.5 million to $ 2 million in compensatory damages and $ 300,000 in compensatory damages for her husband, <PERSON> William </PERSON>. The jury declined to award <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Kociemba </PERSON> any money for loss of consortium as a direct result of his wife's use of the Copper-7. Some 500 lawsuits have been filed over the Copper-7, once the most widely used IUD in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> before it was withdrawn from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market in January 1986. <PERSON> Searle </PERSON> won 14 of the previous 17 cases to be decided, but <PERSON> Kociemba </PERSON> lawyers have said that none of the previous cases included as many documents or deposition testimony as this one. Mrs. <PERSON> Kociemba </PERSON> used a Copper-7 for just under 1 -LCB- years in 1977 and 1978. She claimed the IUD triggered a pelvic infection two weeks after insertion and that the infection scarred her fallopian tubes, leaving her sterile.
