<HEAD>Wickes Adopts Temporary Shareholder Protection Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Wickes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Companies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has adopted a temporary shareholder protection plan that requires potential buyers to keep any offers open through late October, a spokesman said Tuesday. The plan is meant to `` assure shareholders get the best value possible,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Wickes </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>. A management group led by <ORGANIZATION> Wickes </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> <PERSON> Sigoloff </PERSON> has offered to buy the company for $ 12 a share in a $ 598 million leveraged buyout. <ORGANIZATION> Wickes </ORGANIZATION>' stock closed at $ 13.62 -LCB-, down unchanged from Monday's close on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> That plan included a 60-day wait before the group could begin buying shares, in order to give other buyers a chance to emerge. <PERSON> Sigoloff </PERSON>, who led <ORGANIZATION> Wickes </ORGANIZATION> out of bankruptcy proceedings 3 -LCB- years ago, said earlier the management group would not begin buying shares until Oct. 20. The protection plan requires potential buyers keep their offers open through Oct. 20, <PERSON> Stern </PERSON> said, adding the plan was not intended to impede any other offers for <ORGANIZATION> Wickes </ORGANIZATION> shares. The buyout offer has brought numerous inquiries from other buyers, according to <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Tennenbaum </PERSON>, senior managing director at <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which is advising <ORGANIZATION> Wickes </ORGANIZATION> management A buyer of <ORGANIZATION> Wickes </ORGANIZATION> would have to assume $ 2.1 billion in debt. The company's main lines of business are industrial products, including auto fabrics and aircraft and missile parts; home improvement and furnishings, including <ORGANIZATION> Wickes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Furniture </ORGANIZATION> and Builders Emporium do-it-yourself stores in <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>; and a group that makes wallpaper and carpet.
